column86: On January 20, 2020, Canada’s Chief Public Health Officer (Dr. Theresa Tam) and Deputy Chief Public  Health Officer (Dr. Howard Njoo) held their first media briefing on the novel coronavirus    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203170514/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2020/01/government-of-canada-officials-to-hold-a-media-availability-on-a-novel-coronavirus.html

column88: On February 1, the Edmonton Journal reported that 18 individuals have been tested for COVID-19 since January 1, and that the current protocol for testing Albertans for COVID-19 was as follows: "Albertans with possible symptoms who call 811 — and who have recently been to Wuhan, China, or have been in contact with someone who has visited — are given a nasal swab test. Patients with severe symptoms are brought to an isolation room at the hospital, attended by health-care workers wearing masks, protection gowns and gloves, while awaiting test results."     Edmonton Journal article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130042336/https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/risk-of-coronavirus-extremely-low-in-alberta-chief-medical-officer

column74: On February 6, the Alberta Minister of Health asked all travellers coming from Hubei province in China to self-isolate for 14 days upon return. Travellers from other provinces in China do not have to self-isolate but should call Healthlink if any symptoms appear. It does not appear that there is enforcement of this recommendation.    Announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206214843/https://twitter.com/shandro/status/1225447370965389312?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1225447370965389312%7Ctwgr%5E%7Ctwcon%5Es1_&ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fedmonton.ctvnews.ca%2Falberta-urges-self-isolation-for-ill-travellers-returning-from-virus-stricken-part-of-china-1.4800458

column88: A news report on February 26 stated that Alberta has now expanded their COVID-19 testing protocol, which was originally testing only people who had developed symptoms after recently returning from mainland China. The expanded list now includes Hong Kong, Singapore, Iran, Japan, South Korea and Italy as well. It was also noted in the article that 117 tests have been completed so far, with 0 positive cases.    City News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125062211/https://edmonton.citynews.ca/2020/02/26/alberta-health-expands-testing-protocols-as-covid-19-continues-to-spread-across-canada/

column86: Alberta Health Services began providing coordinated public information about COVID-19 in early March, such as a message about how to protect yourself against COVID-19 in a March 4 tweet.    AHS twitter: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204204300/https://twitter.com/AHS_media/status/1235277350318698496

column117: Effective March 5, Alberta has instituted a protected unpaid leave for employees who must quarantine because of COVID-19.    Alberta website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204224048/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-leave.aspx

column88: As of March 7, the COVID-19 testing protocols in Alberta were as listed by Alberta Precision Laboratories (APL):   - Hospitalized and emergency department patients with respiratory virus testing ordered: COVID-19 testing will be added along with the usual respiratory pathogen panel (RPP).  - Hospitalized and emergency department patients with rapid influenza/RSV testing ordered (if available at that site): COVID-19 testing will be performed along with the rapid influenza/RSV test.  - Influenza-like illness(ILI)outbreak patients: COVID-19 testing will be performed, with or without the RPP, depending on what is requested.  - Community patients with respiratory virus testing ordered: either COVID-19 or influenza testing will be performed, depending on what is requested.  - Infection with this pathogen should be considered in patients with fever, cough, and/or shortness of breath who travelled outside of Canada within the last 14 days.  - Symptomatic individuals outside of these criteria may also be considered for testing if, in the clinician’s opinion, there is a reason to suspect COVID-19.    A CBC news article from March 7 also stated that Alberta is looking to expand testing by opening assessment centres in each health zone. Currently people who suspect they may have COVID-19 are instructed to call Healthlink at 811 to determine if a test is necessary, and if it is, a healthcare worker may visit them in their home to provide testing.    APL guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125064256/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/wf/lab/wf-lab-bulletin-novel-coronavirus-causing-covid-19-laboratory-update.pdf  CBC News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125065007/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-19-testing-alberta-1.5488994
column90: A news report on March 7 mentions that Alberta is performing contact tracing for confirmed COVID-19 cases, and contacts all people identified as being 'close contacts' of the cases. The article stated:  "Hinshaw said if someone tested positive, health officials would do 'contact tracing', identifying people the patient had been in close contact with while showing symptoms. 'We would make sure that every person who was named on that list had a phone call from public health,' she said. Everyone on that list of contacts would be asked to stay home for 14 days, whether they were feeling ill or not. Anyone on that list of contacts who shows symptoms would be tested"    CBC News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125065007/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-19-testing-alberta-1.5488994

column115: On March 10, it was reported that the Chief Medical Officer of Health is recommending that  people who feel sick should avoid visits to long-term care homes.    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214022657/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-coronavirus-long-term-care-homes-visitors-1.5492457

column33: On March 12, Dr. Hinshaw, the CMOH has asked that all public gatherings of over 250 people, and any events with more than 50 attendees that include either international participants, critical infrastructure staff or high risk populations be cancelled in Alberta.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128221451/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-coronavirus-gathering-1.5495352
column42: On March 12, Dr. Hinshaw, the CMOH has asked that all public gatherings of over 250 people, and any events with more than 50 attendees that include either international participants, critical infrastructure staff or high risk populations be cancelled in Alberta.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128221451/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-coronavirus-gathering-1.5495352
column74: As of March 12, 2020, all Albertans who are currently travelling outside of Canada should self-isolate on their return for 14 days, independent of the country they were visiting. It is unclear if enforcement is happening to ensure travellers are self-isolating.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128221451/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-coronavirus-gathering-1.5495352

column88: On March 13, Alberta Health Services launched an online assessment tool to help Albertans assess if they are eligible for COVID-19 testing. This is meant to decrease the call volume strain on the Healthlink 811 phone number.    AHS announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130042825/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/releases/2020/Page15435.aspx

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.
column92: On March 15, the government of Alberta announced $500,000,000 CAD ($361.5 million USD) in emergency healthcare investment for COVID-19 response.    Alberta news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206040102/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=69817C344E701-9C80-6249-C7C1432123530CE6

column15: On March 15, the province announced that all schools, including post-secondary institutions would be closed for in-person instruction starting Monday, March 16 for an indefinite period. "School authorities are expected to continue their regular day-to-day operations and ensure the safety of our school facilities. We expect maintenance, capital projects, cleaning of facilities and administrative work to continue." said the Minister of Education. The Minister also noted that all students would receive a final grade and that Grade 12 Diploma exams were cancelled.     Post-secondary campuses will also remain open, although no in-person classes will be held, with all classes moved online.    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125033657/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-coronavirus-update-hinshaw-alberta-edmonton-1.5498467  CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125034104/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/d7e19190-89ac-4383-b148-76aafe905e69/resource/441334a7-5fbb-4230-ab2b-61751064d23e/download/health-cmoh-record-fof-decision-cmoh-01-2020.pdf
column24: On March 15 the province announced that effective March 16, childcare centres are to be closed indefinitely, along with schools and post-secondary institutions.     CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125033657/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-coronavirus-update-hinshaw-alberta-edmonton-1.5498467   CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125034104/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/d7e19190-89ac-4383-b148-76aafe905e69/resource/441334a7-5fbb-4230-ab2b-61751064d23e/download/health-cmoh-record-fof-decision-cmoh-01-2020.pdf
column74: March 16, 2020: Government of Canada banned the entry of all non-Canadian or non-permanent residents into Canada    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203162203/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/mar/16/justin-trudeau-closes-canada-borders-coronavirus

column24: On March 17, Dr. Hinshaw, the CMOH, announced that persons were prohibited from attending "public recreational facilities and private entertainment facilities, including but not limited to, gyms, swimming pools, arenas, science centres, museums, art galleries, community centres, children's play centres, casinos, racing entertainment centres, bingo halls, and bars and nightclubs where minors are prohibited by law."   Restaurants, cafes, coffee shops, food courts and other food-serving facilities, including those with a minors-allowed liquor license were still allowed, with a limit of up to 50% of their capacity, up to a maximum limit of 50 person within the location. Not-for-profit community kitchens, soup kitchens and religious kitchens were also exempt, but had to follow sanitization practices.    CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125043436/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b1efba5f-57ac-44da-a8e0-ceebe6565d72/resource/250393d5-f8a3-409e-9e1a-710e26dbac2d/download/health-cmoh-record-fof-decision-cmoh-02-2020.pdf
column33: On March 17, the CMOH announced that effective immediately all persons in Alberta were banned from attending mass gatherings of more than 50 attendees, including places of worship, gatherings and family events like weddings. Grocery stores, shopping centres, healthcare facilities, airports, the legislature and other essential activities were not included.     CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125043436/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b1efba5f-57ac-44da-a8e0-ceebe6565d72/resource/250393d5-f8a3-409e-9e1a-710e26dbac2d/download/health-cmoh-record-fof-decision-cmoh-02-2020.pdf
column42: On March 17, the CMOH announced that effective immediately all persons in Alberta were banned from attending gatherings of more than 50 attendees, including places of worship, gatherings and family events like weddings. CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125043436/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b1efba5f-57ac-44da-a8e0-ceebe6565d72/resource/250393d5-f8a3-409e-9e1a-710e26dbac2d/download/health-cmoh-record-fof-decision-cmoh-02-2020.pdf
column51: Starting March 17, Edmonton's Transit system is moving to a Saturday, or reduced, schedule every day due to COVID-19.     Global news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129230933/https://globalnews.ca/news/6684783/edmonton-response-transit-coronavirus-covid-19/

column79: On March 18, Alberta announced a deferral on natural gas and electricity payments for individuals who could not work due to the COVID-19 pandemic, either because they were sick, had to isolate or were laid off. Alberta also announced a 6 month interest-free moratorium on student loan payments. Payments can be paused for six months starting on March 30 and students don't have to apply for the repayment pause. The same applies for federal student loan debt. Borrowers can continue making payments during this period if they wish    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130034047/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-announces-50m-for-those-in-self-isolation-deferral-of-utility-payments-1.4858639  Alberta government website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130033542/https://www.alberta.ca/utility-payment-deferral.aspx    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130034613/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/here-s-what-financial-relief-is-available-for-albertans-during-the-covid-19-pandemic-1.5505167

column15: On March 20, the province announced that school authorities would offer at-home learning opportunities for all kindergarten through Grade 12 students in public, separate, Francophone, charter, independent and provincial schools.    Instruction will be provided online, through the distribution of course packages or regular telephone check-ins.    According to a news report the content delivery will be as follows:  - K-3 (5 hours per week): Language/literacy and mathematics/numeracy  - Grades 4-6 (5 hours per week): Core mathematics, language/literacy, potential to include science and social studies  - Grades 7-9 (10 hours per week): Core mathematics, language/literacy, science and social studies  - Grades 10-12 (3 hours per course per week): Specified and core course required for high school graduation requirements    CTV Calgary News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126050121/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/province-releases-plans-for-at-home-education-during-school-closures-1.4861499  Alberta guidance website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126050207/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=69874B5C32DE7-C7B9-FAFF-518A0FF91DCFD41D
column51: Beginning March 20, passengers on Calgary Transit buses must board buses using the rear door, although people with accessibility issues may still utilize the front door for boarding. Calgary Transit Access which operates much smaller vehicles for passengers who cannot use buses or trains due to disabilities, will also start restricting the number of passengers in its vehicles to 2.    Global news: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129222222/https://globalnews.ca/news/6699681/calgary-transit-rear-door-covid-19-coronavirus/
column115: On March 20, Alberta Health Services published guidance that "effective immediately, only one, single essential visitor at a time may visit residents in Long-term Care, Supportive Living and Congregate Living Settings.  •Essential visitors are defined as family, friends or paid companions providing care necessary for  the well-being of the resident and visitors attending to a resident who is dying.  • Each essential visitor must be verified and undergo a health screening prior to entering the facility. This  may include a temperature check or a questionnaire.  • Facilities will have a greeter to conduct this screening and verify all visitors are designated as essential.  • These restrictions apply to all long-term and supporting sites owned & operated by AHS.    Coded as 2G as it is only applied to AHS-owned facilities, and not all long term care facilities.     AHS guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214021315/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/assets/info/ppih/if-ppih-covid-19-staff-guidance-visitor-restrictions.pdf

column88: It was reported on March 21 that Alberta has already completed 20,000 COVID-19 tests, which is the most in the country.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130043756/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-covid-19-tests-more-than-other-provinces-1.5505622

column51: The Calgary Transit website states that 'beginning Monday, March 23, many of our routes will have fewer trips throughout the day. Those routes will still be available, but you may experience longer wait times because a trip has been removed.'    Calgary Transit: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129221523/https://www.calgarytransit.com/news/reductions-transit-service
column88: On March 23, CBC reported on the CMOH announcement of the following changes to testing:     Testing will be prioritized for people with symptoms who fall within any of these groups: people hospitalized with respiratory illness; residents of continuing-care or similar facilities; people who returned from travelling abroad between March 8 and March 12 (before self-isolation protocols were in place); health-care workers with respiratory symptoms.    The statement confirmed that testing will still be done for anyone who has already been told they would get tested. People who returned to Alberta after March 12 and have mild symptoms will no longer be tested for the virus.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130043530/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-health-covid-testing-travellers-1.5506528

column115: On March 24, it was reported that Alberta has limited visitors to long-term care facilities to one essential visitor per resident, and children are no longer allowed to visit.    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214025917/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/calgary-care-home-outbreak-1.5508844

column74: March 25, 2020: The Government of Canada has mandated an immediate 14 day quarantine for all Canadians returning to Canada as of 11:59 pm on March 25, 2020. The Government of Canada has advised that this mandated quarantine will be enforced under the Quarantine Act    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker
column90: On March 25 it was reported that University of Calgary medical students have quadrupled the province's number of contact tracers. University of Alberta medical students will be joining shortly as well as they are currently being trained.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130054555/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/u-of-c-covid-19-contact-tracing-1.5509022

column42: On March 26, it was reported that Dr. Hinshaw provided a suggestion that families could partner with another family to form a cohort. She stated that if this was to happen, the families should only have close contact with each other, not have any risk of being exposed to COVID-19, and should always stay the same. This would apply to families who share custody of children as well.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204225052/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/self-isolation-tips-for-families-from-alberta-s-dr-hinshaw-1.4869813

column24: On March 27, the CMOH ordered, effective immediately, that the following types of non-essential businesses were no longer permitted to provide services to the public at a location accessible to the public:     a) any type of business offering/providing non-essential health services (defined as any service that is generally done to protect, promote or maintain health and where an interruption in provision of services won't result in an individual's life, health, or safety being immediately endangered);  b) any place of business offering/providing personal services;  c) any place of business offering or providing wellness services, including but not limited to massage therapy and reflexology;  d) any retail store, including a retail store in a shopping centre, or other similar place of business offering or providing only non-essential goods or services.  An exception to this rule is if a health professional deems a service as 'urgent' for a), they can offer or provide the non-essential health service.    Restaurants, cafes, coffee shops, food courts and other food-servicing facilities, including those with a minors-allowed liquor license are no longer permitted to offer or provide dine-in services but can operate through take-out, drive-thru or food delivery services.    Global News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125060155/https://globalnews.ca/news/6742251/alberta-health-coronavirus-covid-19-march-27/    CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125053618/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/c02f3b06-9c37-4845-98ee-d07d805fdce1/resource/32f3367d-9a15-4aef-af6e-4e960891c14e/download/health-cmoh-record-of-decision-cmoh-07-2020.pdf
column33: On March 27, the CMOH ordered that effective immediately, any type of public or private gathering in excess of 15 attendees is prohibited whether outdoors or indoors. If a gathering does happen for 15 people or under, they must maintain a minimum of 2 metres distance from one another. This includes, but is not limited to, weddings, funerals, religious services and informal events.    Global News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125060155/https://globalnews.ca/news/6742251/alberta-health-coronavirus-covid-19-march-27/  CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201125053618/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/c02f3b06-9c37-4845-98ee-d07d805fdce1/resource/32f3367d-9a15-4aef-af6e-4e960891c14e/download/health-cmoh-record-of-decision-cmoh-07-2020.pdf

column79: On March 27, Alberta announced that nobody in Alberta would be evicted for non-payment of rent in April. Minister Glubish said "Eviction protection will continue thereafter for the duration of the public emergency for tenants who work with landlords to establish meaningful and reasonable partial payment plans." Tenants who couldn't pay rent in the last few months also cannot be evicted, and landlords can't raise rent during the public state of emergency. If any rent increases were announced recently, they would also be frozen until after the state of emergency is done. No late fees were allowed to be charged between April 1-June 30. This is in addition to the debt relief measures announced on 18 March.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130031904/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/new-landlord-restrictions-announced-in-alberta-as-covid-19-pandemic-continues-1.4871791

column51: The Calgary Transit website states that "beginning Monday, March 30, we will be reducing CTrain service levels. Red Line is reduced to 7 to 8-minute peak service, 15-minute midday service, and 16-minute evening service. Blue Line is reduced to 8-minute peak service and 16-minute non-peak service. Weekend service will not change at this time for either line.  Calgary Transit: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129221523/https://www.calgarytransit.com/news/reductions-transit-service
column60: Alberta's CMOH told Albertans to stay at home on March 30. CTV news reported that Dr. Hinshaw said: "This is also not the time for people to go out to their summer cottages or seasonal villages to self-isolate". The health services and supports are limited so people going from larger centres to smaller communities may overwhelm the health system in those communities.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130013857/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/albertans-should-not-flee-to-vacation-properties-during-covid-19-pandemic-hinshaw-1.4875027
column69: Alberta's CMOH told Albertans to stay at home on March 30. CTV news reported that Dr. Hinshaw said: "This is also not the time for people to go out to their summer cottages or seasonal villages to self-isolate". The health services and supports are limited so people going from larger centres to smaller communities may overwhelm the health system in those communities.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130013857/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/albertans-should-not-flee-to-vacation-properties-during-covid-19-pandemic-hinshaw-1.4875027
column88: AHS has announced that they are about to receive  250 handheld rapid-testing devices, along with 100,000 testing kits, to be distributed to healthcare facilities outside of Calgary and Edmonton to support testing in rural areas. The first shipment of devices and testing kits arrives next month. The rapid testing devices should be able to deliver results in about 1 hour.    AHS announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130043959/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/releases/2020/Page15450.aspx

column15: On April 1, a news article reported that a date for re-opening schools is still unknown. In an interview with the Chair of Edmonton Public Schools it was noted that there was a good chance schools would be shut until the end of the school year.    Global News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126051537/https://globalnews.ca/news/6762309/alberta-classrooms-students-coronavirus-home-year-hinshaw/

column81: On April 2, the province announced $3,000,000 CAD ($2.1 million USD) in funding for school meal programs, to ensure students still receive meals even as school is remote due to COVID-19.    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206051727/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=69985583EED83-0C75-4535-C73FD796C40C1802

column33: The CMOH issued an exemption to the order issued on March 27, which stated that all attendees in outdoor gatherings must be distanced by 2m. The exemption applies to members of the same household, who no longer need to maintain a minimum of 2 metres distance from each other.    CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126043642/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/ec053094-b5a5-41e2-bd9d-a5dfa8ffffcd/resource/573ff959-0421-43a4-a8df-499d38c813c8/download/health-cmoh-exemption-household-gatherings-outdoors.pdf
column42: The CMOH issued an exemption to the order issued on March 27, which stated that all attendees in outdoor gatherings must be distanced by 2m. The exemption applies to members of the same household, who no longer need to maintain a minimum of 2 metres distance from each other.    CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126043642/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/ec053094-b5a5-41e2-bd9d-a5dfa8ffffcd/resource/573ff959-0421-43a4-a8df-499d38c813c8/download/health-cmoh-exemption-household-gatherings-outdoors.pdf

column88: The CMOH has announced expanded criteria for COVID-19 testing. Anyone in Calgary exhibiting COVID-19 like symptoms can now be tested. In addition, any essential worker in Alberta with the same symptoms may be tested, as well as anyone in Alberta living with someone aged 65 or above with the same symptoms.    660 News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130045004/https://www.660citynews.com/2020/04/08/province-expands-covid-19-testing-in-calgary-region/

column51: Calgary Transit announced many reductions in service beginning April 6 to most bus and train routes in Calgary. Most changes relate to longer times between buses/trains, while some include bus stop closures.     Calgary Transit website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129221849/http://www.calgarytransit.com/news/april-6-2020-service-changes
column103: The CMOH said on April 6 that wearing a non-medical face mask “may provide added benefit.” in addition to physical distancing. She also indicated that t wouldn’t protect the person wearing it but could protect others around them in the case of possible asymptomatic spread. Premier Kenney also announced that the government was procuring millions of non-medical masks to distribute to Albertans.    Global news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130064135/https://globalnews.ca/news/6784268/alberta-health-covid-19-kenney-hinshaw-coronavirus-april-6/

column115: On April 7, the province announced that all non-essential visitors were banned from long term care, supportive living, and continuing care residences. No visitors will be allowed unless a resident is dying or the visitor is essential for delivering care that cannot be delivered by staff.    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214020746/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=7002558A018CF-F9A9-099C-85E0C54DE1C3B87C

column60: On April 10, the province urged Albertans to stay at home over the long weekend and to not go camping.  CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130014841/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/stay-home-alberta-health-advises-against-camping-on-the-long-weekend-1.4891519
column81: On April 10, the province announced that it is providing $5 million CAD ($2.57 million USD) to support food banks and community organizations in their food supply efforts, as demand increased due to the COVID-19 pandemic.    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206053810/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=70065F2072F72-D1D5-8FD5-183C93091877A75B

column88: On April 13, it was announced that Alberta is now expanding COVID-19 testing to any Albertan exhibiting symptoms of COVID-19, including cough, fever, runny nose, sore throat or shortness of breath. Albertans should take the AHS online assessment in order to arrange testing and should stay home.    Global news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130044518/https://globalnews.ca/news/6812262/alberta-health-coronavirus-covid-19-april-13/

column92: Alberta announced $53 million CAD ($37.6 million USD) in funding for mental health on April 15. The funding is for "phone and in-person mental health and addiction recovery support to make it easier for Albertans to access services from anywhere in Alberta during and after the COVID-19 pandemic."    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206054657/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=70099FD5A018B-07BD-2B06-3BD3E6BD3108AF41

column15: On April 16, the Calgary Board of Education announced that they were cancelling graduation ceremonies, banquets and school-based celebrations for the 2019-2020 school year in line with the City of Calgary's ban on gatherings that are in effect until at least June 30.    Global News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126052302/https://globalnews.ca/news/6829500/coronavirus-calgary-board-of-education-graduations-cancelled/

column88: On April 17 it was announced that Alberta in expanding testing criteria to asymptomatic individuals in long term care homes that have COVID-19 outbreaks, including both residents and staff.     CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130045859/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-reports-239-more-covid-19-cases-as-province-ramps-up-testing-1.4900806

On April 19, it was reported that Alberta is planning on increasing testing capacity in the near future.    Globe and Mail article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130045445/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/alberta/article-alberta-plans-to-dramatically-expand-a-covid-19-testing-system-that/

column92: On April 20, the Alberta government announced they had put $24,500,000 CAD ($17.4 million USD) for immediate cost pressures in continuing care due to continuing care. They had also noted that extra funding, estimated at about $7.3 million CAD/month, would be provided for: increased health-care aide staffing levels; a wage top-up of an additional $2 per hour for health-care aides; up to 1,000 paid student practicum positions to fast-track certification and get more staff into our continuing care facilities.    Alberta news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206043854/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=70127FF594C5C-CE00-2934-863516C3FEDF723E
column103: April 17, 2020: The Minister of Transport announced measures requiring all air passengers to have a non-medical mask or face covering to cover their mouth and nose during travel. These measures come into effect at noon EDT on April 20, 2020    https://web.archive.org/web/20201119002605/https://www.canada.ca/en/transport-canada/news/2020/04/new-measures-introduced-for-non-medical-masks-or-face-coverings-in-the-canadian-transportation-system.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker

column90: In a news article from April 22, it mentioned there are approximately 440 contact tracers in Alberta dealing with COVID-19 cases and that tracers call each positive case to determine when their symptoms started. Then they ask the individual to provide the information for all close contacts for the 48 hours prior to the beginning of symptoms. They then follow up with each of those cases to ask them to self-isolate and provide more information.    Global news article:   https://web.archive.org/web/20201130054844/https://globalnews.ca/news/6854518/alberta-covid-19-coronavirus-contact-tracing/

column86: As of April 24, Alberta continues to provide coordinated information to the public about COVID-19, including a website with case information and how to protect yourself from COVID-19, an AHS website to provide more information about COVID-19, and daily updates from the Chief Medical Officer of Health (CMOH) and the government on Twitter.    CMOH Twitter: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204222611/https://twitter.com/cmoh_alberta/status/1253811564185923584?lang=en  AB gov't twitter: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204222738/https://twitter.com/youralberta/status/1251656845481082881?lang=en

column115: On April 28, the Chief Medical Officer of Health amended the order barring visitors to long term care settings. The amendment allows up to 2 essential visitors for outside visits only for residents who aren't in self-isolation. Residents may also now designate a temporary essential visitor if their designated visitor cannot perform their role for a certain amount of time.    CMOH order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214031408/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/1a2011e5-fc79-43b4-aab0-1c276b16b99b/resource/35ab8044-8c19-480a-9799-ef4f9b95c376/download/health-cmoh-record-of-decision-cmoh-14-2020.pdf

column15: On April 30, the Premier announced that schools will not be re-opening for the rest of the 2019-2020 academic year. However, it was also mentioned that some schools might open in a limited capacity “on a trial basis.” "That would take into account the possibility of summer classes, specialized programs, providing schools with some more guidance on, for example, the number of students permitted and physical distancing,” Kenney said. School boards were being consulted by the Education Minister. School boards or charter schools submit plans for their individual reopening to the Department of Education and Alberta Health. The province is also considering opening schools earlier than the usual start in September.    Global News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126053827/https://globalnews.ca/news/6890827/coronavirus-alberta-schools-remain-closed-academic-year/

column79: ABLaw.ca reports that the eviction freeze for residential tenants ended on April 30. In place, starting May 1, is a ministerial law saying which imposes on landlords a duty to negotiate payment plans with their tenants before they can be evicted.     ABLaw article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130032632/https://ablawg.ca/2020/04/30/residential-tenancies-in-alberta-evictions-for-non-payment-of-rent-no-longer-suspended/
column90: On May 1, Alberta announced that the provincial contact tracing app, AB Trace Together was ready for use. The app is integrated into the contact tracing team. Tracers will be able to upload the data from the app and contact those indicated as close contacts.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130055154/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/deena-hinshaw-abtracetogether-covid-19-coronavirus-1.5552413

column24: On May 2, golf courses were allowed to reopen in Alberta. Pro-shops and restaurants are to remain closed.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130074914/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/it-s-official-alberta-golf-courses-allowed-to-open-saturday-must-follow-health-guidelines-1.4921710

column88: The CMOH announced on May 5 that asymptomatic close contacts of confirmed COVID-19 cases are now eligible for testing.    Edmonton Journal article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130050533/https://edmontonjournal.com/news/local-news/covid-19-hinshaw-to-give-update-on-covid-19-at-330-p-m

column15: On May 6, the Education Minister said no decisions have been made about whether or not students will return to classes in the fall and outlined three scenarios that are being considered by the province and school authorities:     1) Schools would be open and operating under normal conditions as much as possible.     2) Schools would be "generally open but with some health restrictions in place," such as personal protective equipment or physical distancing guidelines for some classes.     3) Schools would not be open and teacher-directed, at-home learning would continue.    CBC News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126054539/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-education-pandemic-planning-for-classes-to-resume-1.5557267

column24: On May 11, Alberta released guidance around opening some businesses in Stage 1 of the economic relaunch that may happen on May 14. Businesses included in Stage 1 include day camps, daycare, hair salons/barbers, museums and art galleries, outdoor recreation, places of worship, restaurants, and retail shops.    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075236/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-19-alberta-deena-hinshaw-1.5564634
column88: The CMOH announced that anyone in Calgary who works outside the home can now have COVID-19 testing if they have no symptoms. The case count in Calgary is much higher than the rest of the province, so asymptomatic testing may help answer why.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130050209/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/covid-19-cases-in-calgary-increasing-testing-1.5565333

column15: On May 14, Global News reported on plans the major post-secondary institutions had for fall learning. Most institutions, including the University of Alberta, University of Lethbridge, and Mount Royal University planned to offer mostly online classes, with small in-person classes for those classes that were unable to be taught online. The University of Calgary stated that they would offer a combination of online and in-person classes, aiming for about 30% of students to be on campus at one time. The U of C also noted that more information would be available in June for students.  U of A announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126060247/https://www.ualberta.ca/covid-19/updates/05/2020-05-14-update-on-fall-2020-term.html  U of C announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128065402/https://www.ucalgary.ca/news/fall-2020-mixed-delivery-courses-university-calgary    Global News article:   https://web.archive.org/web/20201126055755/https://globalnews.ca/news/6947098/coronavirus-alberta-universities-fall-semester/
column24: As part of the Stage 1 relaunch, businesses including retail stores, restaurants and hair salons opened back up in most of Alberta. Cafes and restaurants were allowed to open at half capacity. Calgary and Brooks were held back from re-opening due to high COVID-19 case counts, and will undergo a more staggered approach.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075531/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/covid-19-business-reopen-relaunch-phase-one-may-14-1.5569070  Alberta relaunch website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx
column60: On May 14, a news report indicated that the province is allowing 'Albertans to conduct "responsible travel to campgrounds, summer homes, cabins and cottages" during the pandemic'. This is restricted to Alberta though, as it is still recommended to not leave the province.  CTV News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130015445/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/can-you-spend-the-long-weekend-at-your-cottage-it-depends-where-it-is-1.4939350
column69: On May 14, a news report indicated that the province is allowing 'Albertans to conduct "responsible travel to campgrounds, summer homes, cabins and cottages" during the pandemic'. This is restricted to Alberta though, as it is still recommended to not leave the province.  CTV News article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130015445/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/can-you-spend-the-long-weekend-at-your-cottage-it-depends-where-it-is-1.4939350

column33: On May 15, the CMOH announced that Alberta is increasing limits on outdoor gatherings to 50 people from 15 as long as proper physical distancing is kept. Indoor gatherings will remain restricted to 15 people, although up to 50 people are allowed to attend indoor worship gatherings.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129015326/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/outdoor-gatherings-of-up-to-50-people-allowed-as-alberta-eases-covid-19-rules-1.5571727
column42: On May 15, the CMOH announced that Alberta is increasing limits on outdoor gatherings to 50 people from 15 as long as proper physical distancing is kept. Indoor gatherings will remain restricted to 15 people, although up to 50 people are allowed to attend indoor worship gatherings.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129015326/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/outdoor-gatherings-of-up-to-50-people-allowed-as-alberta-eases-covid-19-rules-1.5571727"

column15: On May 23, the province published reopening guidance for post-secondary institutions and indicated that in-person classes may now be permitted, although it is recommended that classes still be held remotely and that in-person attendance be limited on campus as much as possible.. The guidance states that 'Post-secondary institutions may resume in-person instruction or blended in-person/online instruction, so long as: a physical distance of two metres is maintained at all times between all individuals who are physically present; the maximum number of people in a room or educational space at one time, with appropriate physical distancing, is 50 people or fewer; if two or more individuals are required to come within two metres of one another for the purpose of instruction, practice, or undertaking examinations, additional protections must be instituted such as engineering controls (barriers or partitions), administrative controls (adapting the activity to minimize or eliminate close contact), or use of PPE by all individuals in close contact.    As Alberta is still in Stage 1 of re-opening, the guidance states that libraries, gyms and indoor recreational facilities, and theatres must still remain closed.     Coded as 3 because as there was no evidence post-secondary institutions re-opened immediately for in-person learning.    Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128053253/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b321eaf7-be50-46b0-a7e2-8022c850512a/resource/ea382bc9-dd5a-43f0-b179-f6f2fae12f7b/download/covid-19-relaunch-guidance-post-secondary-institutions-2020-0614.pdf

column51: Calgary Transit announced further reductions and cancellations of some bus routes in Calgary. "In response to changes in ridership caused by the pandemic, we are making additional reductions to service, beginning Monday, May 25. The reductions include the temporary cancellation of several bus routes and adjustments to service hours and frequencies of others."    Calgary Transit: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129223235/http://www.calgarytransit.com/news/may-2020-service-changes

column24: On May 25 in Calgary and Brooks, hair salons, cafes, restaurants and bars were allowed to reopen at 50 per cent capacity as part of the staggered Stage 1 launch.    Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130080433/https://calgaryherald.com/news/330-update-as-relaunch-nears-who-will-get-green-light-to-open  Alberta relaunch website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx

column88: On May 29, the CMOH announced that asymptomatic testing was available to all individuals in Alberta.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130051001/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-moves-to-provincewide-covid-19-testing-available-to-all-symptoms-or-not-1.5590332

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column24: On June 1, as the last day of Calgary and Brooks' staggered entry into Stage 1, day camps, summer school, post-secondary institutions and places of worship are allowed to reopen.    Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130080433/https://calgaryherald.com/news/330-update-as-relaunch-nears-who-will-get-green-light-to-open  Alberta relaunch website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx

column15: On June 3, Lethbridge School Division released a re-entry brief for precautions that are planned on being taken for school re-openings in Fall 2020 for each of the three possible scenarios that were outlined by the Minister of Education.    Re-entry brief:   https://web.archive.org/web/20201126061402/https://www.lethsd.ab.ca/our-district/news/post/lethbridge-school-division-re-entry-brief
column103: June 3    Today, the Minister of Transport, the Honourable Marc Garneau, announced he is expanding the requirements for the use of face coverings by workers and others involved in the transportation system, to reduce the risk of COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118161447/https://www.canada.ca/en/transport-canada/news/2020/06/minister-garneau-announces-new-measures-for-the-use-of-face-coverings-in-the-canadian-transportation-sector.html

column15: On June 7, the Calgary Catholic School District announced they would offer a small proportion of summer school attendees the option of having in-person instruction. This offer would be made to the about 15% of enrolled students that enrolled in a core course such as Grade 12 Math or English. Students could still complete classes remotely if they were not comfortable with in-person learning.     Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126071546/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/in-class-summer-school-to-be-offered-through-calgary-catholic-school-district

column74: June 8, 2020: The Canada Border Services Agency announced that as of June 8, 2020 23:59 EDT, foreign nationals who are immediate family members of Canadian citizens and permanent residents, and who do not have COVID-19 or exhibit any signs or symptoms of COVID-19, or who do not have any reason to believe they have COVID-19, will be exempt from the prohibition on entry to Canada if entering to be with an immediate family member for a period of at least 15 days    See this as essentially still a full border closure as no commercial flights operating unless in these specific circumstances for individuals who are family members.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.canada.ca/en/border-services-agency/news/2020/06/changes-to-travel-restrictions-for-immediate-family-members-of-canadian-citizens-and-permanent-residents.html

column15: On June 10, the Education Minister stated that the expectation is for students to be back in school in 'near-normal' conditions in September for the start of the 2020-21 academic year. The Minister outlined the three scenarios that were mentioned previously with the first scenario seeing near-normal operations resume with students returning to daily in-school classes with some health measures. Under the second scenario, in-school classes would only resume partially with additional health requirements. The third scenario would see at-home learning continue. The decision about which scenarios to follow will be made by the government based on public-health guidance, the minister said, not by local school boards. The government stated that there would still be health restrictions in scenario 1, with students cohorting by class if possible, physical distancing, and staggering of start/end times, recesses/breaks, and lunches. Alberta also released their 2020 Summer School Re-Entry Guidance on June 10.    Summer School Re-Entry: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126072145/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b44fc139-3891-4e86-b17f-2f40ddd2e70b/resource/ac92cd44-ffde-4d5c-b405-f72f233371ca/download/edc-covid-guidance-school-re-entry-summer-school.pdf    2020-2021 Scenario 1: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126063216/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/3bc9f561-36aa-4ac8-8e73-afce55227c05/resource/482a0c3d-192d-4795-9585-ed76d6c89172/download/edc-covid-guidance-school-re-entry-scenario-1.pdf    2020-2021 Scenario 2: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126063436/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/85be3335-611d-42a3-a607-4f2bd14e7ea8/resource/6aa359fc-5bed-4c2c-ad50-28adc4ce2369/download/edc-covid-guidance-school-re-entry-scenario-2.pdf    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201126062848/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-covid-19-schools-adriana-lagrange-deena-hinshaw-1.5606250

As Alberta moves to Stage 2 of relaunch, K-12 schools can now re-open for exams and summer school as of June 12.    Edmonton Journal article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129020913/https://edmontonjournal.com/news/politics/covid-19-kenney-to-give-update-on-albertas-relaunch-plans-at-1230-p-m

column24: On June 14, Stage 2 of reopening began. Businesses that could open now, with restrictions, include movie theatres, libraries, wellness services like acupuncture and massage therapy, and businesses that provide personal services like manicures/pedicures, waxing, facial treatments and esthetics. Gyms, indoor recreation centres, bingo halls and casinos (without table games), trade shows and concerts were also able to re-open with restrictions. Nightclubs are prohibited.    Alberta re-opening website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx  CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130081453/https://globalnews.ca/news/7044126/jason-kenney-stage-2-relaunch-announcement-june-9/
column33: As part of Stage 2 relaunch, Alberta is now allowing larger public gatherings, like 100 people allowed at outdoor events and indoor seated/audience events, including wedding ceremonies, funeral services, movie theatres, indoor arts and culture performances and other indoor spectator events where people remain seated. 50 people are allowed at indoor social gatherings, including wedding and funeral receptions, and birthday parties. There are no longer any caps, as long as public health guidance is being followed, at the following: worship gatherings, restaurants, cafes, lounges and bars/casinos/bingo halls/exhibits and trade shows.    Alberta re-opening website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx
column42: As part of Stage 2 relaunch, Alberta is now allowing larger public gatherings, like 100 people allowed at outdoor events and indoor seated/audience events, including wedding ceremonies, funeral services, movie theatres, indoor arts and culture performances and other indoor spectator events where people remain seated. 50 people are allowed at indoor social gatherings, including wedding and funeral receptions, and birthday parties. There are no longer any caps, as long as public health guidance is being followed, at the following: worship gatherings, restaurants, cafes, lounges and bars/casinos/bingo halls/exhibits and trade shows.    Alberta re-opening website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130075948/https://www.alberta.ca/alberta-relaunch-strategy.aspx

column15: The University of Lethbridge released an update on Fall classes with mostly online, but some in-person classes. The two main reasons why most classes remain online were given as follows: "safeguarding the health and safety of our students, staff and faculty, and ensuring the quality and stability of the academic experience."    U of L announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128070919/https://www.uleth.ca/notice/notices/covid-19-%E2%80%94-fall-2020-timetable-update-%E2%80%94-experiential-person-classes
column51: ETS will start allowing front door boarding and fare collection on June 15. Fares were not collected from March 20, when a state of emergency was called. Passengers are encouraged to wear a mask.    Global news: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129233829/https://globalnews.ca/news/6999220/covid-19-edmonton-relaunch-ets-fares-reintroduced/

column69: In a news report on June 17, it is mentioned that Alberta Health is still recommending against inter-provincial travel, although Dr. Hinshaw stated it is a recommendation and not a legal requirement.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204201342/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/to-b-c-or-not-to-b-c-albertans-split-on-idea-to-leave-the-province-this-summer-1.4989029

column79: On June 19, the deferral program for electricity and natural gas payments has ended.    Alberta government website: Alberta government website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130033542/https://www.alberta.ca/utility-payment-deferral.aspx

column15: The province released updated guidance on re-opening post-secondary institutions on June 22. Capacity limits are raised to 100 from 50, and libraries, gyms and theatres are now able to open with the relevant public health measures.    Alberta Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128054748/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/b321eaf7-be50-46b0-a7e2-8022c850512a/resource/ae10e2a0-49de-4ec2-b441-9d16f2efe185/download/covid-19-relaunch-guidance-post-secondary-institutions.pdf
column51: Calgary Transit started distributing masks to passengers starting June 22, and also started added plexiglass barriers in order to increase ridership. column15: On June 23, the U of C provided more guidance on Fall 2020 classes. column115: On July 16, the CMOH announced loosened restrictions for visitors for licensed supportive living (including group homes and lodges), long-term care (nursing homes and auxiliary hospitals), and facilities offering or providing a residential hospice service model. Residents were now allowed to designate two support people who will be able to visit indoors, for as long and as often as they want. Outdoor visits are also allowed with up to four people. In some circumstances, when it is safe, those other visitors may also be allowed to visit indoors, if a facility has a designated indoor visiting space. Each facility could make its own policy around visitors to fit their own specific circumstances. column15: On July 21, the province announced the School Re-Entry Plan for 2020-21. column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column88: On September 17, the CMOH announced a change in testing protocols with cold and flu season approaching. Testing will be prioritized for any person exhibiting symptoms of COVID-19, all close contacts of confirmed COVID-19 cases, and all workers and/or residents at specific outbreak sites.  Voluntary asymptomatic testing is also being offered to: school teachers and support staff; health care workers; staff and residents at congregate living facilities, including long-term care; Albertans experiencing homelessness; travellers who require testing prior to departure. Asymptomatic testing will be available to additional groups if required, and anyone who is not showing symptoms but is concerned about their health should speak to the health care provider.    The reason for the change was to reduce wait times for testing and results, and because asymptomatic testing over the last several months only yielded about 7 cases/10,000 tests.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130053238/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/province-changes-covid-19-testing-approach-for-asymptomatic-albertans-1.5109847
column115: On September 3, the CMOH announced new updates to long term care restrictions, which will be effective September 17. In this update, residents who leave their facility for extended outings (longer than a day outing) may no longer have to quarantine upon their return. Previously, all residents had to, even if their outing was very low risk. The new guidance allows residents returning from medium- or low-risk outings to be under less stringent precautions applied, such as continuous masking or enhanced symptom monitoring. Volunteers will also be permitted back onsite.    CMOH guidance and order: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214041703/https://open.alberta.ca/dataset/7680fe82-f705-43e2-9fbe-979f6b0847b0/resource/4b2168f6-7324-40db-8387-29f27fc930ff/download/health-cmoh-record-of-decision-cmoh-32-2020.pdf    CBC article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214042208/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-eases-covid-19-restrictions-on-residents-of-continuing-care-homes-1.5710991

column15: On September 18, the CMOH reported the first case of COVID-19 that was believed to be contracted in a school. Dr. Hinshaw reported the case was contracted at Waverley School in Edmonton. “To date, AHS has identified two cases that were infectious while in the school, one of whom seems to have been the source for the other.”     Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204085138/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/covid-19-main-3

It was reported on Sept 22 that about 3000 students are currently self-isolating from the Calgary Board of Education, Calgary Catholic Schools and the Edmonton Public Schools systems. There is evidence of in-school transmission of COVID-19 in 3 schools in Alberta as well.     CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201127053034/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/calgary-self-isolation-students-1.5733498

column24: On September 23, the CMOH announced that indoor recreation, entertainment and play areas were allowed to re-open. The province also issued guidance for safe re-opening.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201207015159/https://calgary.ctvnews.ca/alberta-allows-indoor-play-areas-to-reopen-as-colder-conditions-near-1.5117089  AB guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201207015301/https://www.alberta.ca/assets/documents/covid-19-relaunch-guidance-indoor-recreation-entertainment-play-centres.pdf

column15: The University of Alberta, University of Calgary and University of Lethbridge announced their plans for the Winter semester on September 24. Classes will be a combination of online and in-person. From the U of A announcement:  "For Winter 2021, we will continue to prioritize in-person learning where it is essential for program completion or progression; and, we will explore all opportunities to increase our current roster of in-person course offerings on our campuses to maximize student learning (lectures, graduate research, practicums, experiential placements, etc.) up to 30% within public health guidelines. Decisions about Winter 2021 in-person experiences will be made in consultation with deans and academic leaders. A detailed list of Winter 2021 in-person offerings will be available in mid-November."    U of C announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128064420/https://www.ucalgary.ca/news/update-winter-term  U of L announcement:   U of A announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128062553/https://blog.ualberta.ca/from-the-presidents-desk-announcement-on-the-winter-2021-semester-dad0e650b765?gi=876134917dbf
column42: On September 24, Alberta issued guidance for holiday gatherings, to prepare for Thanksgiving. The guidance includes having one person plate everyone’s meals so people are not sharing serving utensils, and that the person serving should wash or disinfect their hands before and after serving, and should wear a mask.    Guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129054609/https://www.alberta.ca/assets/documents/covid-19-relaunch-guidance-safe-holiday-entertaining.pdf

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

Canada Emergency Response Benefits ended on 26 September.    Other support still in place- detailed here:    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155358/https://www.canada.ca/en/services/benefits/covid19-emergency-benefits.html    This article  suggests that after the CERB ends, eligibility for receiving other kinds of support will be widened, so I have left this coding as a 2F ("The government has announced the implementation of certain measures to make it easier to access EI benefits for workers who, until now, have been eligible to receive the CERB. Some of these measures incorporate the bulk of legislative changes brought to the Employment Insurance Act (Emergency Response Benefit) under Interim Order No. 7") and (The federal government plans on introducing three new income support benefits to replace the CERB for workers not eligible for EI.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155613/https://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/en/knowledge/publications/8df5a679/what-to-expect-after-the-canada-emergency-response-benefit-comes-to-an-end

column69: After a search, there seems to be no recommendations against travelling within Alberta, or to other provinces. Alberta guidance recommends 'responsible travel'.    Alberta COVID-19 website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201204221755/https://www.alberta.ca/covid-19-travel-advice.aspx

column15: On Oct 2, it was reported that there were active alerts (one case) or outbreaks (two or more cases) at 133 schools (numbers provided on Oct 1), which represents about five per cent of schools in Alberta.  There were 257 active cases among those who attend these schools. There were 52 schools with outbreaks, including seven on the "watch" list, meaning they have five or more cases. Dr. Hinshaw said the vast majority of school-aged kids appear to have acquired COVID-19 outside of the school setting. column103: On October 5, Strathcona County made masks mandatory in all public spaces. Previously, masks were only mandatory on transit buses and in County buildings. Masks are recommended in all indoor work settings and a limit of three cohorts is advised. If they continue to be above 50, the mandate will stay in place. column15: On Oct 30, Alberta removed runny nose and sore throat from the daily symptoms checklist for parents to use to assess their children daily before school for any symptoms of COVID-19, and to take the proper actions, like keeping their children home and getting them tested for the virus, if necessary. This was done after reviewing experiences in Alberta and other provinces from this academic year so far. The new checklist will go into effect as of November 2. column42: On November 6, Alberta introduced tighter recommendations in areas where the active case rate for the region was identified as 50 or greater (per 100,000 population) or where the active cases for the region was identified as 10 or greater. Albertans, especially those in Edmonton and Calgary, were asked to not hold gatherings at home. The recommendation is not mandatory so will not be enforced. Banquets and receptions should still also be limited to 15 people. Premier Kenney said "Now just is not the time to host parties or large extended family dinners. Until cases slow, we must press pause on hosting any gatherings involving people outside your core family or immediate household."    CBC news: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129072554/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/edmonton/alberta-covid-19-public-health-measures-1.5792919
column90: Effective November 6, due to rapidly rising COVID-19 cases, AHS will only be performing contact tracing in 3 situations: hospitals, schools and continuing care homes. All positive cases will still be called to find out if they belong to one of the three groups. If they don't, they will be asked to notify their own close contacts. AHS is in the process of hiring hundreds more contact tracers to help.    CBC news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130062547/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/calgary/alberta-ahs-craig-jenne-deena-hinshaw-covid-19-1.5791839  AHS announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130062702/https://www.albertahealthservices.ca/news/Page15694.aspx

column33: Effective immediately, all indoor social gatherings are banned across the province. Outdoor gatherings are limited to 10 people. Weddings and funerals will be limited to 10 people. Receptions are prohibited. Those who live alone are allowed to have two non-household close contacts. Violations could result in a ticket up to $1,000 or a $100,000 penalty through the court system. column15: On November 27, the University of Alberta announced that the start of Winter term would be delayed to January 11 with mostly remote learning, and some in-person classes. column24: On November 24, Alberta announced new restrictions and a State of Emergency. Starting November 27, event venues like banquet halls, conference centres, community centres and indoor play spaces, in enhanced-status areas will be closed for in-person business.    Retail and businesses like grocery, clothing, pharmacy technology and hardware stores in enhanced-status areas will be allowed to remain open but must restrict their capacity to 25%, or a minimum of five customers, whichever is higher. The 25% capacity limit also applies to event and entertainment businesses such as theatres, libraries, museums, bingo halls, and water and amusement parks. It also applies to fitness, recreation and activity centres, although group fitness classes, training or team practices are prohibited.    Restaurants, bars, pubs and lounges may stay open but must follow public health orders. Tables are limited to a maximum of 6 people who must be from the same household. No movement is allowed between tables. If a person lives alone, they can eat out with up to 2 close contacts. No other services like entertainment and games are allowed in these businesses, and the previous rule mandating liquor sales stop by 10 p.m. and businesses close by 11 p.m. has been extended.    Casinos are only allowed to operate slot machines and must stop table games, and must also follow the same liquor sales and closure rules. Personal, wellness, hotel and professional services are no longer allowed to serve walk-ins, and can only remain open by appointment only.    The premier also asked that any workers who can work from home do so for at least three weeks. Masks were also made mandatory on November 24 in all indoor workplaces in the Edmonton and Calgary zones, where the bulk of Alberta COVID-19 cases are located.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128045747/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-bans-indoor-gatherings-introduces-new-restrictions-for-schools-and-businesses-1.5202390    Alberta guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128075143/https://www.alberta.ca/enhanced-public-health-measures.aspx

column15: On November 24, it was announced that starting Nov 30, all grade 7-12 students in Alberta will move to online learning in order to help reduce the spike of COVID-19 cases. Students will remain in online learning until December 18 when schools start their holiday breaks. When school returns on January 4 2021, all K-12 students in Alberta will start school in remote learning for the first week, and move back to in-person classes on January 11 to give extra time at home in case any students are exposed to COVID-19 around the holidays. All students with disabilities who require support and services in any grade whose needs cannot be met through at-home learning and students in outreach programs can continue to receive supports and services in-person at school, regardless of the shifts to at-home learning before and after the winter break.    CTV news article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128045747/https://edmonton.ctvnews.ca/alberta-bans-indoor-gatherings-introduces-new-restrictions-for-schools-and-businesses-1.5202390  Alberta school guidance: https://web.archive.org/web/20201128045901/https://www.alberta.ca/k-to-12-school-re-entry-2020-21-school-year.aspx

column77: CERB (Canada Emergency Response Benefit) has closed as of 2 December, 2020. Thus, I have downgraded the supports available to <50% of income. column106: Alberta announced their COVID-19 vaccination plan on December 2. "Immunization will be phased, starting with Phase 1 in early January, once vaccines are received. Those vaccinated in Phase 1 include long-term care and designated supported living residents and staff in those facilities, on-reserve First Nations individuals over age 65, seniors aged 75 and older, and health-care workers most needed to ensure workforce capacity and who are most likely to transmit COVID-19 to those at greatest risk.    Phase 2 is expected to begin by April 2021 and will again be targeted to prioritized populations. Phase 3 will involve rolling out vaccinations to the general Alberta population, anticipated to start by fall 2021."    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206223911/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=758197B34E45E-950B-4D01-C2EF320F08ED2A03

column15: On December 3, the University of Lethbridge announced that the holiday break would be extended by 3 days. Previously, classes were to resume January 6, and now will resume January 9 2021. The university president stated: "...we are very aware that as students go home, they may be in contact with others throughout the holiday season, including New Year’s Eve. With more in-person classes being offered in the spring, this proposal allows for more time to elapse between New Year’s and the start of in-person classes to reduce the risk of transmission among faculty and students on campus. The safety of our campus community and southern Alberta as a whole is still foremost in our decision-making"    ULeth announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214005857/https://www.uleth.ca/unews/article/university-lethbridge-extending-holiday-break-effort-enhance-campus-well-being

Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214043011/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/in-the-second-wave-covid-19-cuts-another-swath-through-continuing-care-homes

column24: On December 8, it was announced that closures announced on November 27 would be extended for: entertainment businesses and entities – community halls and centres, indoor children's play centres and indoor playgrounds, theatres, auditoriums, concert halls, and community theatres, nightclubs, banquet halls and conference centres, indoor and outdoor festivals, concerts with the exception of drive-in events, trade shows, and sporting events or competitions.    In addition, effective December 13, mandatory work from home measures will be implemented unless the employer determines that work requires a physical presence for operational effectiveness. Restaurants, pubs, bars, lounges and cafes will also be closed to in-person service, with only takeout, curbside pickup and delivery services permitted. Casinos, bingo halls, gaming entertainment centres, racing entertainment centres, horse tracks, raceways, bowling alleys, pool halls, legions, and private clubs will be closed. Recreational facilities – fitness centres, recreation centres, pools, spas, gyms, studios, day and overnight camps, indoor rinks and arenas – will be closed. Entertainment businesses and entities – libraries, science centres, interpretive centres, museums, galleries, amusement parks and water parks – will be closed. Personal and wellness services, including hair salons, nail salons, massage, tattoos, and piercing, will be closed.    Outdoor recreation will still be permitted, but facilities with indoor spaces except for washrooms will be closed. Hotels may remain open but must follow restrictions – no spas, pools or in-person dining. Room services only. Health services, including physiotherapy or acupuncture, social or protective services, shelters for vulnerable persons, emergency services, child care, and not-for-profit community kitchens or charitable kitchens will remain open for in-person attendance. Retail services must reduce customer capacity to 15 per cent of fire code occupancy, with a minimum of five customers permitted. Curbside pickup, delivery and online services are encouraged. Shopping malls will be limited to 15 per cent of fire code occupancy.    These restrictions will be in place for at least 4 weeks.    Government news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213232349/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=75859ADEA5D5E-045D-2386-0CB140C175A800DD
column33: On December 8, the province announced that effective immediately all social gatherings are prohibited, whether indoor, outdoor, public or private. In addition, festivals, parades, events, concerts, exhibitions, competitions, sport and performance remain prohibited. This restriction will be in place for a minimum of 4 weeks. This will be enforced with a $1,000 CAD fine.    Effective December 13, places of worship will be restricted to 15% of fire code occupancy for in-person attendance. Virtual or online services are strongly encouraged. Drive-in services where individuals do not leave their vehicles and adhere to guidance will be permissible and are not subject to capacity restrictions. Mandatory mask mandate, physical distancing and other guidelines remain in place    Government news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213232349/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=75859ADEA5D5E-045D-2386-0CB140C175A800DD
column42: On December 8, the province announced that effective immediately all social gatherings are prohibited, whether indoor, outdoor, public or private. "Close contacts are limited to household members only. Individuals who live alone will be allowed up to two close contacts for in-person visiting, with those two people remaining the same for the duration of the restriction period." This restriction will be in place for a minimum of 4 weeks. This will be enforced with a $1,000 CAD fine.    Government news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213232349/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=75859ADEA5D5E-045D-2386-0CB140C175A800DD
