column81: On December 8, Alberta announced an expansion of the Small and Medium Enterprise Relaunch Grant. An additional $300,000,000 CAD ($234,160,127 USD) is added to the grant, and is now expanding to include job creators who have experienced a 30 per cent revenue loss due to the COVID-19 pandemic. This lowers the threshold from the existing requirement of 40 per cent revenue loss. The 30 per cent threshold will be available to impacted businesses retroactive to March. As announced on November 23, businesses impacted by recent restrictions may apply for a second payment. This second payment will now be 15 per cent of pre-pandemic monthly revenues up to a maximum of $15,000 – for a total of $20,000 in potential funding available for each business, up from the original $5,000. Applications will be open until March 31, 2020.    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214015152/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=75857AD8FABE4-FC8C-5401-C9D635A7F9FFE8C0
column103: The province announced that effective December 8, masks were mandatory in all indoor public spaces and workplaces in Alberta. Previously, mandatory masking in public places was left up to municipal governments, and the province had made masks mandatory in schools from grades 4-12, and in workplaces in Calgary and Edmonton zones.   "Public spaces include locations where a business or entity operates and is applicable to employees, visitors and the general public; applies to all indoor workplaces and facilities outside the home; farm operations are excluded; rental accommodations used solely for the purposes of a private residence are excluded".  The restriction will be in place for a minimum of 4 weeks.  Government news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213232349/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=75859ADEA5D5E-045D-2386-0CB140C175A800DD

column15: On December 9, in a response to the government restrictions announced the previous day, the University of Alberta announced that the on-campus activities related to recreation will be shut down, no meetings will be allowed, and dining options will be changed to adhere with new restrictions that shut down in-person dining. Residences will remain open for students living on campus. column86: On December 11, it was announced that Alberta was starting an ad campaign targeted at individuals between the ages of 20-40, which involved a personified version of COVID-19. The Chief Medical Officer of Health (CMOH) stated: "Bending the curve is also why we have launched a new, light-hearted marketing campaign that uses humour to reach Albertans under 40 and anyone else who may have tuned out our other messaging". The ads will be on television, as well as on various social media sites, and also has a corresponding website which provides information on what COVID loves and does not like, as well as guidance, and myths/facts about COVID.    CMOH announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213231208/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=7589448B552CE-CE8E-26AD-8BDB8BDB9C2CD94C    Campaign website: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213231245/https://covidloves.ca/    Calgary Herald article: https://web.archive.org/web/20201213231359/https://calgaryherald.com/news/local-news/covid-19-loves-the-holidays-according-to-new-alberta-psas

column15: On December 10, the University of Calgary how the December 8 restrictions will affect the university. Effective December 13, the fitness centre, pool and recreational facilities must close; all Active Living group programs are suspended; the University Athletics suspension first announced on Nov. 26 will continue; all university libraries must close. This means students cannot access post-secondary libraries for any purpose, although they can do front door pick-ups and drop-offs of books and materials; Study spaces outside of libraries will remain open to solo study only. Group studying is not allowed except in situations where two or more students must be physically present for the purpose of practice or a practical activity (e.g., lab practice, massage practice). Students should opt for virtual study groups instead. If two or more students must be physically present to practise a specific activity, the students should stay two metres apart from each other at all times and be masked. Students who must come within two metres of each other for practice, rehearsal, or study must wear a mask, even if they are outdoors.    The performance activity exemption for school settings also applies to post-secondary institutions. However, although performance practices and rehearsals can occur, performances, concerts, and inter-school performance activities are not allowed at this time.    Streaming a live performance for an exam is permissible if there is no live audience involved.    All social gatherings in indoor workplaces, such as lunchroom gatherings, are not allowed.  Food courts will only be permitted to provide take out; there will be no use of tables and seating permitted    U of C announcement: https://web.archive.org/web/20201214010406/https://www.ucalgary.ca/news/impact-new-government-covid-19-restrictions-campus

column106: A: On December 15, vaccinations began for healthcare workers in Alberta. In this first phase of the vaccination, which included 3900 Pfizer vaccine doses, respiratory therapists, intensive care unit physicians and staff, and eligible long-term care and designated supportive living workers are to be given the vaccine at the delivery sites in Calgary and Edmonton. The Alberta news release stated that a "further 25,350 Pfizer vaccine doses are expected to arrive in Alberta on Dec. 21", which would be distributed to healthcare workers across the province. Other groups are expected to be included in Phase 1 of the vaccination plan in early January: "As more shipments arrive in early January, immunization will focus on Phase 1 priority populations and will include residents of long-term care and designated supportive living facilities, followed by seniors aged 75 and over, and First Nations on reserve, Inuit and on-settlement Métis individuals aged 65 and over."    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201222033246/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=759141713475A-D564-5B29-768BE62C2253473C
column117: On December 15, Alberta announced there would be additional supports for citizens who lived in 2 communities in Calgary and 9 communities in Edmonton that were hit hard by COVID-19. "Individuals in these areas who test positive for COVID-19 will be eligible for a free-of-charge hotel room stay of 14 days, complete with culturally appropriate food. The individuals will also be eligible for temporary financial aid in the amount of $625 when they have completed their self-isolation."    COVID Care Teams will also be dispatched to the communities:  "These community-led outreach teams will provide on-the-ground supports and interventions to limit the spread of the virus; care packages with masks, sanitizer, and information in multiple languages will be delivered in these areas; safe transportation to COVID-19 assessment and testing facilities will be available. Outreach will be led and supported by community leaders and local faith and settlement organizations. Translators will also provide support if necessary".    AB news release: https://web.archive.org/web/20201222050138/https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=7591213FD4097-ACE5-AED2-40355B77AA35E600

column103: BC's support for masks took a long time. On April 1st B.C.’s provincial health officer said that she is “not against” the widespread use of non-medical masks as the world grapples with the novel coronavirus pandemic. This was phrased as a personal choice and not a full recommendation.     To quote: "Non-medical cloth masks are your choice during COVID-19. A non-medical cloth mask or face covering, while helpful in containing your own droplets, will not protect you from COVID-19, nor is wearing one required of you if you can keep your safe distance from others. Moreover, using a cloth mask does not give you permission to disregard physical distancing and self-isolation orders. Indeed, these, along with respiratory etiquette and hand hygiene, remain the key proven measures to stop transmission.    Wearing a cloth mask or face covering is a matter of personal choice. It is another tool you can choose, particularly when maintaining that important safe distance can be a challenge."     On July 23rd, in the face of mounting opposition BC's top doctor said that there were no plans for ‘heavy-handed’ mandatory mask policy (article below).     Only July 29th While other jurisdictions have imposed mandatory mask orders, B.C. has encouraged their use without requiring them.    On June 30, provincial health officer Dr. Bonnie Henry said B.C.’s level of coronavirus transmission did not necessitate a mask order. Henry said she has been hesitant to order British Columbians to wear masks because doing so is “not a viable option” for some.    The voluntary nature of mask wearing was repeated on Oct 9th: "The provincial health officer has ruled out a mandatory mask indoor order.    On Thursday, Dr. Bonnie Henry said she continues to advocate voluntary wearing of non-medical masks indoors when it’s hard to socially distance — or on public transit — but she would not order it."    It was not until October 26th that a clear recommendation to wear masks inside was made.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201113184336/https://globalnews.ca/news/6763036/bc-coronavirus-update-april-1/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201113172529/https://news.gov.bc.ca/factsheets/non-medical-cloth-masks-are-your-choice-during-covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130211824/https://globalnews.ca/news/7211415/coronavirus-mandatory-masks-bc/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201104124841/https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/07/29/bc-covid-19-masks/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201020032346/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/covid-19-one-death-and-110-new-cases-as-b-c-passes-10000-case-milestone
column115: No COVID protection measures for the elderly or care homes were put into place in January 2020.    On Jan. 27th 2020, our BC Centre for Disease Control public health lab locally confirmed a presumed positive test for 2019-nCoV. On Jan 29th 2020 the following statement was issued: The risk of spread of this virus within British Columbia remains low at this time. All necessary precautions are being taken to prevent the spread of infection. We have multiple systems in place to prepare for, detect and respond to prevent the spread of serious infectious diseases in the province.    It is not necessary for the general public to take special precautions beyond the usual measures recommended to prevent other common respiratory viruses during the winter period. Regular handwashing, coughing or sneezing into your elbow sleeve, disposing of tissues appropriately and avoiding contact with sick people are important ways to prevent the spread of respiratory illness generally.     https://web.archive.org/web/20200808000358/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020HLTH0016-000176

column74: On January 20th passengers at the Vancouver International Airport encountered new screening measures as Canadian health officials keep a close eye on China's coronavirus outbreak. The Public Health Agency of Canada said it would introduce messaging over the coming week on arrivals screens reminding travellers from Wuhan, China — the site of the outbreak — to inform a border service officer if they experience flu-like symptoms.     Quarantine measures were in debate until February. An example of this is that on Jan 31 more than 150 Canadians were waiting to be evacuated from China, and the question of quarantines was part of an ongoing discussion on how to best contain the virus – but on Jan 31st the position of B.C.'s provincial health officer was that imposing a quarantine would be unnecessary.      https://web.archive.org/web/20200814060512/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/yvr-coronavirus-screening-1.5433477    https://web.archive.org/web/20200501162559/https://globalnews.ca/news/6444560/bc-health-officials-airport-screening-coronavirus-united-states/    https://web.archive.org/web/20200301161644/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/why-b-c-s-top-doctor-doesn-t-want-to-impose-a-coronavirus-quarantine-1.4792625
column86: On January 20, 2020, Canada’s Chief Public Health Officer (Dr. Theresa Tam) and Deputy Chief Public  Health Officer (Dr. Howard Njoo) held their first media briefing on the novel coronavirus    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203170514/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2020/01/government-of-canada-officials-to-hold-a-media-availability-on-a-novel-coronavirus.html

The first warning about COVID19 came from public officials on January 21st 2020. column115: On February 11th 2020 there was a statement made to reassure people that the risk of this virus spreading within B.C. remained low at this time. The ask was for people who have recently visited, or who have been in close contact with, someone who has recently visited the Hubei province in China to call public health officials and self-isolate for 14 days. None targeted advise for general hand hygiene was being given.     https://web.archive.org/web/20210104184610/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020HLTH0028-000258

column74: On February 7th, a quarantine was put in to place for those who'd been in China's Hubei province. Anyone who has travelled to Hubei province should self-isolate for 14 days and contact public health officials for support.     From March 12th anyone who chooses to travel should self-isolate for 14 days.     On March 17th, all persons coming into BC must quarantine for 14 days: until April 8th this was not the case if the international traveller entered into another Canadian province. The act was updated to move from a targetted BC entry needing to quarantine towards a general principle that any entry into Canada within 14 days needed 14 days of self isolation.  As of March 25, 2020 it is mandatory under the Quarantine Act that anyone arriving in British Columbia from outside of Canada self-isolate and monitor for symptoms for 14 days upon their arrival.    On April 8th, BC introduced new measures to make sure British Columbians returning home from international destinations have the support they need to self-isolate. The measures, which include a new legal requirement to provide a self-isolation plan, support the provincial health officer’s travel orders and reinforce the federal emergency order under the Quarantine Act requiring people entering Canada to self-isolate for 14 days. Effective on April 8 2020, international travellers (including from the United States) coming to the province are required to provide a self-isolation plan before or upon arrival to B.C., regardless of their point of entry to Canada. This document, which can be submitted online or completed in person on arrival, must show that returning travellers have supports in place to safely self-isolate for 14 days.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200208153712/https://www.nationalobserver.com/2020/02/07/news/coronavirus-british-columbia    https://web.archive.org/web/20201102082428/http://www.bccdc.ca/resource-gallery/Documents/Guidelines%20and%20Forms/Guidelines%20and%20Manuals/Epid/CD%20Manual/Chapter%201%20-%20CDC/COVID19-Self-isolation-for-contacts-travellers.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20201014170151/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/b-c-health-officials-discouraging-all-non-essential-travel-outside-canada-1.4850891    https://web.archive.org/web/20201105090242/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/b-c-recommends-against-all-non-essential-travel-outside-canada-as-7-new-cases-of-covid-19-detected-1.5495811    https://web.archive.org/web/20200930053200/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-1.5494135    https://web.archive.org/web/20200414164426/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/public-safety-and-emergency-services/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/gdx/orders-april-10/pho_class_order_travellers_and_employers_april_10_2020.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20200414164426/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/public-safety-and-emergency-services/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/gdx/orders-april-10/pho_class_order_travellers_and_employers_april_10_2020.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20201123171118/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/self-isolation    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021081727/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020PREM0019-000657    https://web.archive.org/web/20200604090546/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/travelling-into-b-c-from-outside-the-country-you-re-now-legally-required-to-have-a-self-isolation-plan-1.4888283

column115: On February 29th a statement was given stating that the risk of spread of COVID-19 within British Columbia remains low at this time, and BC officials were focusing their efforts on containing and delaying the spread of transmission. column115: On March 4th and 5th B.C. health officials have said that their focus remains on containing the virus, but have acknowledged that they are preparing for a full-blown pandemic, given the rapid spread of COVID-19 to countries around the world. In a statement on the 5th it was stated that: "public health teams continue to identify and notify close contacts of all active cases. They will be supported to self-isolate for 14 days and are being monitored for symptoms. We are continuing widespread testing by screening British Columbians and travellers with symptoms, along with their close contacts, to identify cases of COVID-19 and take immediate action as we have seen today." The following day more measures were brought in after the first care home resident contracted the virus. As well, a rapid escalation after long term care facilities had an outbreak on March 7th.     https://web.archive.org/save/https://globalnews.ca/news/6632386/bc-covid-update-wednesday-march-4/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201222153431/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/covid-19-bc-timeline-1.5520943    https://web.archive.org/web/20200330050219/https://www.straight.com/life/1369276/bc-confirms-eight-new-covid-19-cases    https://web.archive.org/web/20201104022509/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020HLTH0062-000393    https://web.archive.org/save/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/6-new-cases-of-covid-19-in-b-c-including-2-long-term-care-home-residents-1.4843279?cache=yes%253Fclipid%253D104056%253FcontactForm%253Dtrue%253Fot%253DAjaxLayout

column115: On March 6 2020 theB.C government activated the advanced COVID-19 response to protect British Columbians. At the time of this announcement on March 6th the BC government was in Phase 1 of the plan, which addressed identification and containment -- continuing strong public health testing and close collaboration with the federal government on border surveillance, to identify and isolate individuals who test positive for the virus and their close contacts. At this point the priority was to delay the onset of widespread community transmission for as long as possible.    The following day saw the first outbreak in a long term care home on Mar. 7, 2020, regional health authorities in British Columbia sent specialized health teams comprising infection control practitioners, public health staff and clinicians to all homes with outbreaks under their governance, irrespective of facility ownership. PPE was distributed to care homes.  British Columbia announced visitor restrictions on Mar. 13 2020 to essential visitors only. Strict controls in care facilities with regards to hygiene were put in place before this announcement restricting visitation.     On March 25th 2020, On Mar. 25, 2020, British Columbia issued a directive that all LTC staff and visitors should wear masks within LTC homes. The following day British Columbia announced a single-site LTC work policy to stop people from moving between facilities.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201214183830/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/health/about-bc-s-health-care-system/office-of-the-provincial-health-officer/reports-publications/covid-19-pho-order-movement-health-care-staff.pdf  https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7721263/  https://web.archive.org/web/20200817095015/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/covid-19-outbreak-declared-over-at-lynn-valley-the-hardest-hit-seniors-home-in-b-c/  https://web.archive.org/save/http://www.bccdc.ca/Health-Professionals-Site/Documents/PHSA-labtesting-archived-summary.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20200928193517/http://www.bccdc.ca/Health-Professionals-Site/Documents/COVID19_ppe_allocation_framework.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20200930154520/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/assets/gov/health/about-bc-s-health-care-system/office-of-the-provincial-health-officer/reports-publications/covid-19-infection-prevention-control.pdf  https://web.archive.org/web/20210104181220/https://bccare.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/COVID19_LongTermCareAssistedLiving_V8_March-13-2020.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20201028201354/https://www.broadbentinstitute.ca/bc_s_swift_response_to_long_term_care_crisis_sets_the_bar_for_other_provinces    https://web.archive.org/web/20210104181349/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020PREM0012-000404

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.

column88: Phase 2 of the testing procedure started on March 16. It set up that targeted testing of individuals with respiratory symptoms who are most vulnerable to severe illness and the people who work with these individuals:     (a) hospitalized or likely to be hospitalized patients,   (b) health care workers,   (c) residents of long term care facilities, or   (d) part of an investigation of a cluster or outbreak.    On March 22nd St Paul's launches testing increasing capacity to 2136 tests per day. On March 23rd Life labs begins testing at locations across the province.     On April 2nd Outpatient COVID test results made available.         https://web.archive.org/web/20201123204716/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/testing/phases-of-covid-19-testing-in-bc    https://web.archive.org/web/2/http://www.bccdc.ca/about/news-stories/stories/2020/the-story-of-b-c-s-leading-edge-covid-19-test-development    https://web.archive.org/web/2/http://www.bccdc.ca/about/news-stories/stories/2020/the-story-of-b-c-s-leading-edge-covid-19-test-development    https://web.archive.org/web/2/http://www.bccdc.ca/about/news-stories/stories/2020/the-story-of-b-c-s-leading-edge-covid-19-test-development

column24: On March 17th the province of British Columbia declared a public health emergency. This was to allow Provincial Medical Health Officer Dr. Bonnie Henry the ability to be "faster, more streamlined and nimble". In the announcement specific sectors were shut down such as bars.     On March 21 more establishments were closed indefinately. This was the start of what is now considered "Phase 1" which enabled industries designated as “essential services” to operate safely in the early stages of BC’s COVID-19 response, while closing down all other services. On March 26th all but essential services were closed.     https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-march-17-1.5499835    https://web.archive.org/web/20201027201750/https:/covid.smallbusinessbc.ca/hc/en-us/articles/360047697294    https://web.archive.org/web/20200920151813/https:/www.theglobeandmail.com/canada/british-columbia/article-bc-orders-personal-service-establishments-closed-including-salons/    https://web.archive.org/web/20200920002103/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020HLTH0102-000540

Events over 50 people are banned, effectively cancelling many public events. On April 20th the festival of lights is cancelled as they are unable to operate with the restrictions in place. Officials tell BC to not expect large public events for the remainder of 2020. column60: On March 17th, British Columbia declared a public health emergency and ordered to cancel all gatherings of more than 50 people. Citizens were urged to stay home if possible, and municipalities were asked to close non-essential community hubs. column117: A state of emergency was declared under the Emergency Program Act: This declaration will make sure federal, provincial and local resources are delivered in a joint, co-ordinated effort to best protect British Columbians. The Province previously declared states of emergency in 1998, 2003, 2017 and 2018 – all related to wildfires. In each of those previous declarations, necessary actions were able to be taken without issuing minister’s orders under the Emergency Program Act.    https://archive.news.gov.bc.ca/releases/news_releases_2017-2021/2020PSSG0020-000568.htm#:~:text=A%20new%2C%20Provincial%20Supply%20Chain,%2C%20air%2C%20marine%20and%20rail.

Youth in care will not age out during the COVID19 crisis and those who have recently aged out will get extra assistance. Young adults between the ages of 19 and 27 who are enrolled in the Agreements with Young Adults (AYA) program will continue to receive financial support despite school closures and other training program interruptions caused by the current pandemic. If applicable, these young adults may also be eligible to receive an extension of AYA support beyond the current maximum of 48 months. Youth who are nearing the end of an Independent Living or Youth agreement will be given options allowing them to continue receiving monthly living expenses past their 19th birthday    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021082426/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020CFD0042-000596

column79: From April 1st more specific contract relief was granted to BC households. Much of the relief is dedicated to businesses (as is seen in the articles below and the BC Auditor's report). The narrow measures provided seem to stop being available at the end of August. Business supports continued through the summer.   Three examples include:    1) BC Hydro COVID-19 Relief Fund available from April 1 2020 until June 30 2020. It provided eligible residential and small business customers with three months of financial relief on their BC Hydro bill. In the same period customers who weren't eligible for the COVID-19 Relief Fund, we offered the COVID-19 Customer Assistance Program, which allowed you to defer bill payments or arrange for flexible payment plans with no penalty.      2) The Civil Rights Tribunal recognized that the COVID-19 situation may have limited the ability of respondents to receive or respond to Dispute Notices. In the interest of fairness, the CRT did not process requests for default decisions and orders between March 18 and May 31, 2020.     3) To support people and prevent the spread of COVID-19, the Province is introducing a new temporary rental supplement, halting evictions and freezing rents, among other actions.      The new rental supplement will help households by offering up to $500 a month towards their rent, building on federal and provincial financial supports already announced for British Columbians facing financial hardship. The program ended on August 31, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021112433/https://www.bchydro.com/news/conservation/2020/covid-19-updates.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20201022233654/https:/news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020AG0030-000651    https://web.archive.org/web/20200918125257/https:/civilresolutionbc.ca/covid-19/#default-decisions-and-orders    https://web.archive.org/web/20201022235457/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020FIN0024-000754    https://web.archive.org/web/20201114002329/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020MAH0048-000561    https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://www.bchousing.org/BCTRS

column88: April 9th was the start of phase 3 in testing. This expanded testing to priority populations for whom results would change their care or the management of the case:    (a) residents of remote, isolated or Indigenous communities,  (b) people living and working in congregate settings (e.g. correctional facilities),  (c) people who are homeless or have unstable housing,  (d) essential service providers (e.g. first responders), or  (e) returning travellers identified at a point of entry to Canada.    On April 20th 2020 it was announced that the following day testing was to change towards identifying and addressing any new community clusters and outbreaks. Anyone with COVID-19 symptoms can now be assessed and tested through a physician, nurse practitioner or a local community collection centre.  There is no longer a requirement to be referred by a health care provider or by calling 8-1-1. If you have no symptoms -- including health care workers, those who are a contact of a confirmed case or a returning traveller -- you do not require a test.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200804185013/https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-canada-british-col/early-testing-helps-canadas-british-columbia-fight-coronavirus-cases-elsewhere-soar-idUKKCN21R3DI    https://web.archive.org/web/20201123204716/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/testing/phases-of-covid-19-testing-in-bc    https://web.archive.org/web/20201022230046/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020EMBC0020-000729    https://web.archive.org/web/20201120105613/http://www.phsa.ca/staff-resources/covid-19-resources-for-staff/staff-covid-19-testing    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118032721/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/testing/testing-information

column117: A new collaborative framework will help ensure people living in rural, remote and Indigenous communities in B.C. have access to critical health care they can count on to meet their unique needs during the COVID-19 pandemic and into the future.  The framework was developed through a partnership between the First Nations Health Authority, Northern Health and Provincial Health Services Authority. The work is guided by the principles of cultural safety and humility, and adds to work underway by the Rural Coordination Centre of BC. The framework provides flexibility so local leaders in rural, remote and Indigenous communities can adapt it to meet their unique needs. It will be implemented through full engagement with each of the communities’ local leaders.     https://web.archive.org/web/20200929080834/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020PREM0020-000725

column88: On April 21st phased 4 of testing started. This meant symptom-based testing of all individuals with symptoms compatible with COVID-19, however mild. testing was changed towards identifying and addressing any new community clusters and outbreaks. Anyone with COVID-19 symptoms can now be assessed and tested through a physician, nurse practitioner or a local community collection centre.  There is no longer a requirement to be referred by a health care provider or by calling 8-1-1. If you have no symptoms -- including health care workers, those who are a contact of a confirmed case or a returning traveller -- you do not require a test.    This continues to be the policy as of December 2020, as the article below states "If an individual has no symptoms, they do not require a test. In B.C., testing is generally not available through the provincial health care system for people without symptoms including routine screening for employment, travel, school, before surgery or for other health procedures. This advice may be different from other provinces or countries. In select situations, such as investigation into an outbreak, people without symptoms may be tested under the direction of a medical health officer or clinician.'.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201123204716/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/testing/phases-of-covid-19-testing-in-bc    https://web.archive.org/web/20201122120253/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/testing

column90: Every time someone tests positive for COVID-19, tracers interview that person to determine when they became contagious, where they travelled, who they were in contact with, and what symptoms developed.    They trace a person’s movements for 48 hours before they noticed symptoms — the current best estimate for when health officials believe a person can start spreading COVID-19. Officials pepper people with questions: Do they work with any high-risk groups like senior citizens? What transportation methods do they use to get around? Who lives in close contact with them? Who are their coworkers? Who are they sleeping with? What stores have they shopped in?    From there, even more inspectors branch out to interview all those contacts, in some cases putting out public pleas for anyone on a certain bus or in a certain store at a certain time to get tested.    Everyone notified must go into quarantine and monitor their symptoms. If any of them test positive — and test results are now available within 24 hours, say officials — the contract tracing process is repeated again for that person’s contacts, expanding the investigative web outward.    Track and trace continues to be comprehensive as of December 2020. As per the article below, COVID-19 cases are tracked by the province's health authorities working in collaboration with public health officials by actively contact tracing cases and their close contacts.    VCH public health follows up directly with every person in our region who tests positive for COVID-19. If a person is a close contact of someone who has a confirmed case of COVID-19, then a member of VCH’s public health team will contact them as well to let them know. Cases and contacts will be asked to self-isolate, so they don’t spread illness to others. Contract tracing helps diagnose people earlier to reduce the chance of spreading COVID-19. If you have been identified as a COVID-19 case or close contact, please know that VCH will contact you directly and provide further instructions.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200603025810/https://vancouversun.com/news/local-news/covid-19-b-c-ramps-up-contact-tracing-to-track-down-spread-of-coronavirus    https://web.archive.org/web/20201109050813/http://www.vch.ca/covid-19/covid-19-faqs

column117: The $50-million Connecting British Columbia program now includes a funding stream to help internet service providers with immediate network equipment upgrades to rapidly improve capacity and internet speeds in underserved communities throughout the province. Internet service providers throughout the province can apply for grants of up to $50,000 – or 90% of their expenses – to cover the cost of equipment, including antennas, electronics or other types of devices that relate to the performance or range of their network. Applications are now being accepted by Northern Development Initiative Trust. Submissions will be reviewed on a first-come-first-served basis, with funding decisions made within three to five business days. Internet service providers must complete their projects by June 30, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200921004521/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020CITZ0008-000751

The provincial state of emergency is being extended for the third time, to support the extraordinary measures taken by the Province under the Emergency Program Act to keep people safe during the COVID-19 pandemic.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201025024720/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020EMBC0022-000783

The B.C. government is deferring one of the fees it charges to help people, communities and forest companies navigate through the COVID-19 crisis.    Stumpage, the fee operators pay the Province to harvest, buy or sell trees from Crown land, is being deferred for three months.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021081117/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020FLNR0026-000786

The province is allowing local government to hold public hearings electronically during the current provincial state of emergency. Under the Emergency Program Act, the Province has repealed and replaced Ministerial Order M083 with M139 to expand the authorities given to local governments under M083. The new order will help local governments, improvement districts and the Islands Trust continue to make important decisions for their communities during the COVID-19 pandemic, including allowing local governments to hold public hearings electronically.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201022235742/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020MAH0025-000802

The Province is opening a 45-bed emergency response centre with wraparound supports and services at Save-On-Foods Memorial Centre, the first site in B.C. to feature pop-up pods that provide privacy for people staying there.    The new temporary accommodation site will house people living in encampments on the Pandora Avenue corridor and Topaz Park in Victoria.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201022234816/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020SDPR0025-000818

New Buy BC e-commerce funding is available to help the province’s farmers and food and beverage processors overcome some lost sales during the COVID-19 pandemic by moving their products online.    The B.C. government is providing $300,000 to support industry-led Buy BC e-commerce activities. The funding is under the Ministry of Agriculture’s Buy BC Partnership Program. It helps farmers, ranchers and food and beverage processors market their products as locally grown, raised, harvested or produced, making it easy for British Columbians to Buy BC.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021081621/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020AGRI0017-000857

The plan signals a business has done their homework and we can visit their store, enjoy a meal or workout with confidence. If they had this plan done they were not required to close. Some industries, such as movie theaters, are not open until phase 3.     https://web.archive.org/web/20200921231609/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/phase-2

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column117: Hospitality licensees are allowed to sell their existing liquor stock to other licensees who are still operating and/or to private liquor stores. This authorization is set to expire on July 15, 2020. Also on June 5th The Province is extending a temporary ministerial order until Dec. 31, 2020, to continue to allow health-care workers and other public sector staff to use communication tools not normally permitted for use during the COVID-19 state of emergency.    On March 26, 2020, Anne Kang, Minister of Citizens’ Services, approved a ministerial order under the Freedom of Information and Protection of Privacy Act (FOIPPA) to temporarily permit the use of vital software and technologies in the public sector that have proven useful in B.C.’s successful efforts to flatten the curve. The order allows:    patient-care teams to use multiple communication tools, including things like smartphones, text messaging, chat programs and other applications during their response to the public-health emergency. This has made it easier to communicate between teams and follow up with patients using virtual platforms;  people in self-isolation to communicate with public health officials using chat apps they are most comfortable with, rather than having to learn how to use something new; and  K-12 schools and post-secondary institutions to provide online and digital learning platforms, so students can continue their studies while gatherings of 50 people or more are prohibited.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201023002705/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020AG0040-001016    https://web.archive.org/web/20201021081256/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020CITZ0010-001019

Government has introduced the COVID-19 Related Measures Act, legislation that will allow for the provisions created for citizens and businesses in response to the pandemic to be formalized and unwound as appropriate after the provincial state of emergency ends. Currently, all ministerial orders made by the solicitor general under the Emergency Program Act (EPA) end immediately at the conclusion of the provincial state of emergency. Specific orders already made will be extended in the legislation after the end of the state of emergency by 45 or 90 days. Given the possibility of a second wave of COVID-19, the act will also provide the possibility for extension of COVID-19 related orders by up to one year after the act is brought into force, if required. The act will also incorporate current ministerial emergency orders so the legislature may pass and formally recognize them.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201023000945/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020AG0043-001126

column24: BC enters into phase 3: throughout this period previously closed sectors begin to open. The ban on the amount of people who can gather (under 50) is still in place, so all places of business need to follow this rule in order to open. These relaxed workplace closure measures are in place over the summer, but by the start of September a rise in case numbers happens. These means that more variation starts to happen with workplace closures in September and November while in "phase 3".     https://web.archive.org/web/20201120110446/https://globalnews.ca/news/7138115/bc-movie-theatres-reopen-coronavirus/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118194911/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/phase-3    https://web.archive.org/web/20201120110446/https://globalnews.ca/news/7138115/bc-movie-theatres-reopen-coronavirus/
column33: Coded as a 2G as only very low numbers of people can meet (under 100)    On June 24th BC entered into phase 3. In phase 3 of the COVID-19 restart plan non-essential travel is allowed. This relaxation allows for public events to take place, but strict measures are still in place limiting the size of any gathering. The government and health ministers have also told BC that the summer will be extraordinary and recommend not returning to normal. The guidelines allow for events to take place if they are COVID secure, but there are strong recommendations for social distancing and caution. The decision to hold public events that are COVID secure will be up to the providers, but many public events have looked at the public health guidance and decided to cancel or adjust their plans.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201031163523/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/b-c-enters-phase-3-of-covid-19-restart-plan-allowing-non-essential-travel-1.4997774    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118194911/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/phase-3    https://web.archive.org/web/20200902032747/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-june-24-1.5624836    https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-phase-3-changes-1.5625863    https://web.archive.org/web/20201113083812/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/update-covid-19-bc-july-22-1.5656611
column42: On June 24th phase 3 began but large gatherings were still not permitted for gatherings over 50.     On July 22nd, With an increased spike, more measures were put back into place and no more than 6 people could meet at a restaurant. Restrictions on gatherings still remained at under 50.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200902032747/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/coronavirus-update-bc-what-you-need-to-know-june-24-1.5624836    https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/bc-phase-3-changes-1.5625863    https://web.archive.org/web/20201113083812/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/update-covid-19-bc-july-22-1.5656611
column60: On June 24th BC moved to phase 3, which relaxed measures further. At this time no stay at home requirements are in place.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118194911/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/phase-3
column69: On June 24th BC entered phase 3, which saw the easing of travel restriction recommendations to allow for internal movement. Advice continued to to be cautious, and encouraged people to consider not taking trips for non-essential travel. To quote: "Certainly, if you’re coming to British Columbia, be mindful of what British Columbians have done together to get us to a position where we can welcome people from other parts of the country". This easing across the province found that some regions, particularly remote regions, started discussing targeted restrictions against visitors from outside the community.  Therefore, these phase 3 restrictions gave the general advice not to travel, but allowed the tourism sector to open and receive visitors. Requests to be respectful of different communities willingness to receive them was made clear however. Until the end of July there were movements between communities without official restrictions.     https://web.archive.org/web/20200926062309/https://www.destinationcanada.com/sites/default/files/archive/1096-Canadian%20Resident%20Sentiment%20and%20Travel%20Related%20Measures%20-%20July%208%2C%202020/COVID-19%20Canada%20Resident%20Sentiment%20and%20Travel%20Related%20Measures_July%208_FINAL_EN.pdf    https://web.archive.org/web/20200923220605/https:/covid.smallbusinessbc.ca/hc/en-us/articles/360047698694-Phase-3-Current-Phase-
column117: State of emergency over COVID-19 reinstated for 8th time in B.C. The state of emergency will now be in place until at least July 7.     https://bc.ctvnews.ca/state-of-emergency-over-covid-19-reinstated-for-8th-time-in-b-c-1.4997855

Province of British Columbia has extended the temporary layoffs provisions to a maximum of 24 weeks expiring on Aug. 30, 2020, during the COVID-19 pandemic. The extension will give employers and workers additional flexibility to support economic recovery in the province with the expectation that businesses honour their obligations to workers and reach agreement with their employees in the event a further extension is required. Section 72 of the B.C. Employment Standards Act provides a tool unique in Canada, allowing employers and workers to extend temporary layoffs by making a joint application to the Employment Standards Branch.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200929064625/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020LBR0018-001174

column115: Widespread policies for based on age are not in place, but for those in long term care facilities strict measures are in place. These measures include visitation for essential reasons only, and only by one family member. Strict hygiene and isolation measures are in place in British Columbia. These include cleaning procedures, screening, hand hygiene, respiratory hygiene, source control and physical distancing. Staff movement is also being limited to reduce the risk of transmission.      Below is the Infection Prevention and Control Requirements for COVID-19 in Long Term Care and Seniors’ Assisted Living published on June 30th 2020.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201231021709/http://www.bccdc.ca/Health-Info-Site/Documents/COVID19_LongTermCareAssistedLiving.pdf

column69: In July phase 3 restrictions are place with general advice not to travel, but allowing the tourism sector to open and receive visitors. column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column117: Starting on Sept. 28, 2020, following consultation with the Supreme Court of B.C. and key stakeholders, the attorney general is amending the Rules of Civil Court to temporarily suspend all civil jury trials for a period of one year. Under this temporary suspension, civil jury trials will resume on Oct. 4, 2021, with any trial taking place before this date to be heard by a judge alone. In addition, neither plaintiffs nor defendants will be permitted to adjourn cases to a later date in order to have the matter heard by a jury, unless the court orders otherwise.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201030145100/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020AG0059-001775

column115: Widespread stay at home orders for the elderly are not in place: including during the public health order between Nov 19th and Jan 8th. However, those in Long-Term Care and Assisted Living Facilities are currently advised to restrict visitors. Under these guidelines (the link below being updated last on October 5th) residents will be able to visit with one family member or friend. The guidelines support visits between family members and residents of long-term care homes and seniors’ assisted living facilities while protecting vulnerable residents. These visitors can be for essential reasons only, which includes:  Visits paramount to the patient/client’s physical care and mental well-being, including as follows:  Assistance with feeding mobility or  personal care;  Communication assistance;  Assistance by designated representatives for persons with disabilities;  Visits for supported decision making;  Police, correctional officers and peace officers accompanying a patient/client for security reasons.  Essential visits shall be limited to one visitor per patient/client within the facility at a time (except in the case of palliative/end of life care). A visitor who is a child may be accompanied by one parent, guardian or family member.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201231021710/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-professionals/clinical-resources/covid-19-care/clinical-care/long-term-care-facilities-assisted-living    https://web.archive.org/web/20210102214514/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/restrictions

column42: On November 19th a provincial wide order came in to force limiting social gatherings. Social interaction and getting together with others in person and online is important to our wellbeing. At this time, British Columbians must limit in-person social gatherings to the people they live with. This is not the time to invite friends or family over to your home and do not go to someone else’s home for a social visit. Using technology, such as video calls, to keep in touch with friends and family is a good option right now. The order is, as of Dec 4th, in effect until December 7, 2020 at midnight.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201128230059/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/social-interactions
column60: All of British Columbia is now under provincial wide restrictions that health officials imposed last week on the Lower Mainland. Provincial health officer Dr. Bonnie Henry announced Thursday that all B.C. residents are urged to socialize only with fellow household members and to avoid social gatherings of all kinds and sizes for the next two and a half weeks. It is recommended to not go far from home, and groupings of 6 at venues such as restaurants are in place and to stay within your core bubble. You can travel for work but not for leisure.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201125210142/https://vancouverisland.ctvnews.ca/b-c-announces-new-restrictions-on-social-gatherings-travel-provincewide-1.5196709    https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/what-you-need-to-know-bc-restrictions-covid-nov-19-1.5809318    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201235907/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/what-you-need-to-know-bc-restrictions-covid-nov-19-1.5809318    https://web.archive.org/web/20201220154453/https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/safety/emergency-preparedness-response-recovery/covid-19-provincial-support/restrictions
column69: On November 19th broad restrictions across the province were put in to place by an order and direction of the Provincial Health Officer (PHO), all events and social gatherings are suspended to significantly reduce COVID-19 transmission related to social interactions and travel. column103: "Ordering universal mask use in all situations creates unnecessary challenges with enforcement and stigmatization."    Those were the words of  Provincial Health Officer Dr. Bonnie Henry. And not in April or September but two days before Thursday, November 19th in a letter published in many media outlets.     But that was Tuesday, and this is Thursday.    And after months of debate and surging cases, Henry finally "broke the fire extinguisher glass" to combat B.C.'s COVID emergency.    Masks are now mandatory in virtually all public spaces, and a host of other rules and guidelines are also in place.    As outlined in the mask mandate order, masks are required for everyone in many public indoor settings. A face shield is not a substitute for a mask as it has an opening below the mouth. Masks are required in many indoor public settings and all retail stores. Emergency Management BC is reviewing other community locations where a mask mandate may be advisable and anticipates issuing a further order to enforce requirements for masks in common areas of apartment buildings, condos and workplaces.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201116033852/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/masks-should-be-worn-inside-all-public-spaces-b-c-health-officials-say-1.5162036    https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://globalnews.ca/news/7423664/coronavirus-bc-masks-in-public/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201205050/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/covid-masks-bc-mandate-november-2020-1.5809260    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129184013/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/prevention-risks/masks

column103: As outlined in the mask mandate order, masks are required for everyone in many public indoor settings. A face shield is not a substitute for a mask as it has an opening below the mouth. Masks are required in many indoor public settings and all retail stores.    The mandate was announced last week by provincial health officer Dr. Bonnie Henry, but several of the details were still being worked out. On Tuesday, officials confirmed the mandate applies to "many indoor public settings," including:     malls, shopping centres, coffee shops, and retail and grocery stores;   liquor and drug stores;   airports, city halls, libraries, community and recreation centres;   restaurants, pubs and bars;   places of public worship;   on public transportation, in a taxi or ride-sharing vehicle;   common areas of office buildings, court houses, hospitals and hotels;   common areas of sport and fitness centres when not engaged in physical activity; and   common areas of post-secondary institutions and non-profit organizations.  Everyone 12 years and older is expected to wear a mask, though there are some exceptions. People who are unable to put on or remove a mask on their own don't have to wear one, nor does anyone who "may not be able to wear a mask for psychological, behavioural or health condition, or due to a physical, cognitive or mental impairment."    As of Nov 24th people can be fined $230 for violating B.C.'s new mask mandate.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201116033852/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/masks-should-be-worn-inside-all-public-spaces-b-c-health-officials-say-1.5162036    https://web.archive.org/web/2/https://globalnews.ca/news/7423664/coronavirus-bc-masks-in-public/    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201205050/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/covid-masks-bc-mandate-november-2020-1.5809260    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129184013/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/prevention-risks/masks    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130223039/https://bc.ctvnews.ca/people-can-be-fined-230-for-violating-b-c-s-new-mask-mandate-1.5203312    https://web.archive.org/web/20201201183110/http://www.bccdc.ca/health-info/diseases-conditions/covid-19/prevention-risks/masks#:~:text=disposing%2520of%2520masks-,When%2520to%2520wear%2520a%2520mask,people%252012%2520years%2520and%2520older.

column117: B.C. government announced changes to the Small and Medium-Sized Business Recovery Grant program to make it easier for businesses to qualify. They have also increased support for businesses in the tourism sector.    Adjustments made to the Small and Medium-Sized Business Recovery Grant program include:    Businesses impacted by the pandemic will be eligible to receive between $10,000 and $30,000 in a non-repayable grant. The additional amount available to tourism-related businesses has been increased up to $15,000. This amount is available on top of the base grant, for a total of up to $45,000.  Instead of requiring a revenue loss of 50% or more, the criteria has been reduced to 30% at the time of application;  the requirement to list a variety of remittance accounts, like the registration numbers for the goods and services tax, provincial sales tax and WorkSafeBC, have been removed;  businesses that have been in operation for the last 18 months are now eligible (reduced from three years);   applications can now be submitted by sole proprietors, with fixed costs; and   businesses that are temporarily closed or seasonal are now eligible for the  program.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210101073809/https://news.gov.bc.ca/releases/2020JERI0044-002118

column106: A; Pfizer BioNTech, Moderna:    The first vaccine schedule has stayed the same. By Jan 11th 2021 two vaccines have been approved: on December 9, 2020 was the Pfizer-BioNTech vaccine, on December 23, 2020 the Moderna vaccine was authorized for use. Dec. 30 is the first day Moderna’s COVID-19 vaccine is available for First Nations communities in the province. This is because Dr. Henry states that "“As soon as [Moderna] arrives, it will be going to a number of remote and isolated First Nations communities that have been identified”. This is because Moderna’s vaccine has “different storage and handling requirements” compared to the Pfizer vaccine, meaning it can be distributed to isolated and remote communities    Vaccination will happen in phases. The first groups to get vaccinated between December and February include:    residents, staff and essential visitors to long-term care and assisted-living residences.  individuals in hospital or community, awaiting a long term care placement.  health care workers providing care for COVID-19 patients in settings like Intensive Care Units, emergency departments, medical/surgical units and paramedics.  remote and isolated First Nations communities.     Clinically vulnerable groups will not be prioritized in the first roll out. Those over 80 years old are expected to get it in the second roll out between  February to March. There is some exception to only key workers getting the vaccine if a person is in hospital and needs to be given long term care placements. As well, remote indigenous communities are in the first wave. Generally though the first roll out is targeted at key workers, or those in a essential caring role, and not along age or underlying conditions.     The amount of supply available to British Columbia is not sufficient for the demand. During a Monday (January 11, 2021) briefing, Dr. Henry asked for patience, adding that the province’s entire supply of the Pfizer vaccine is expected to be used by day’s end.    While B.C.’s Pfizer-BioNTech doses may be used up by end of day Monday, the West Coast is still set to receive 28,275 doses of that vaccine the week of January 11-17 and the two weeks to follow.    https://web.archive.org/web/20210112001231/https://www.citynews1130.com/2020/12/31/first-nations-moderna-vaccine-bc/    https://web.archive.org/save/https://dailyhive.com/vancouver/moderna-covid-19-vaccine-arrive-bc    https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.ctvnews.ca/health/coronavirus/covid-19-vaccine-arrives-in-remote-first-nations-across-canada-1.5260824

column77: Effect March 1, 2020, the government implemented a temporary exception to employment standards regulations to give employers more time to recall employees laid off as a result of COVID-19. Under this policy, announced March 27, 2020, any period of layoff occurring after March 1, 2020 will not be counted toward the period after which a temporary layoff would become a permanent termination.    Workers who are temporarily laid off may also have options to access streamlined federal employment benefits at this time.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201108123654/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/index.html?item=47284
column86: The Government of Manitoba continues to encourage caution and self-monitoring of symptoms.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108093847/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46891
column88: No policy change noted in updated provincial bulletins:     https://web.archive.org/web/20201108093847/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46891
column90: No policy change noted in updated provincial bulletins:     https://web.archive.org/web/20201108093847/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46891

column92: On March 10, 2020, the Government of Manitoba announced the planned purchase of Personal Protective Equipment for the province's COVID response at an estimated cost of 35.2 million CAD.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108101147/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46925    Later reports estimated the actual cost of emergency investment in healthcare totaled 64M CAD by March 25, 2020:    "The minister noted as part of the ongoing battle against COVID-19, the province has, to date, invested emergency spending of almost $64 million in critical goods and services including personal protective equipment, ventilators, intravenous pumps and chest compression systems."    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108115255/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/index.html?item=47257

column15: Schools urged to "consider implementing virtual or online classrooms, which reduces the number of people in classrooms and increases distance between staff and students."    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108101928/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46933
column24: Businesses urged to "work from home if possible" and encourage "virtual meetings to reduce prolonged, close contact between individuals."    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108101928/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46933

column33: "Social distancing measures include cancelling or postponing any large-scale events with more than 250 attendees.  This measure helps reduce prolonged (more than 10 minutes), close (less than two metres) contact between other individuals in public."    https://web.archive.org/web/20201108101928/https://news.gov.mb.ca/news/?archive=&item=46933
column42: "Social distancing measures include cancelling or postponing any large-scale events with more than 250 attendees.  This measure helps reduce prolonged (more than 10 minutes), close (less than two metres) contact between other individuals in public."
