Schools located in the following Public Health Unit regions can resume in-person instruction on January 11, 2021 for both elementary and secondary students:    The District of Algoma Health Unit  North Bay Parry Sound District Health Unit  Northwestern Health Unit  Porcupine Health Unit  Sudbury and District Health Unit  Thunder Bay District Health Unit  Timiskaming Health Unit  For schools in all other Public Health Unit regions, elementary school students are planned to be able to return to in-person learning on January 11, 2021, and secondary school students will continue learning remotely until January 25, 2021, at which point they may resume in-person learning. column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.

On 14 April, the Ministry of education announced a number of measures to assist with post secondary students on the Island in jobs and research funding:   Minister Fox also announced enhancements through the Jobs for Youth Program to community, environment, and non-government organizations to create 280 student employment opportunities.    To help Island business retain their current employees, Minister Fox announced an increase to private sector wage subsidies through the Employment Development Agency. The subsidy will increase from 50 per cent of wages to 75 per cent of wages.Minister of Economic Growth, Tourism and Culture Matthew MacKay announced an expansion of the Post-Secondary Employment Program through Skills PEI. The program supports 100 per cent of student wages for government and non-government organizations and will now support 75 per cent wage funding for the private sector, up from 50 per cent. The Post-Secondary Employment Program will create up to 320 new positions.  To increase the COVID-related supports provided by the province’s post-secondary institutions to students in immediate need, Minister of Education and Lifelong Learning Brad Trivers announced a total of $95,000 to support the UPEI Student Union, Holland College and Collège de l'Île.    In addition, Minister Trivers announced a partnership with the University of Prince Edward Island to develop a $75,000 research fund for students wishing to pursue opportunities in their respective fields of interest.      https://archive.vn/Yb9eD    $95,000 CAD = ~70,000 USD

column81: on 16 April, PEI announced up to $66million CAD for support for the tourism industry:   Minister of Economic Growth, Tourism and Culture Matthew Mackay announced a new $50 million tourism assistance loan facility through Finance PEI, with maximum financing of up to $1 million at 4 per cent interest available for working capital. column15: The Province has outlined it's plans to safely return students to school in September.   Colleges and UPEI remain closed: https://archive.vn/wip/EytX5    The plan includes guidelines for all schools to keep students and staff safe, for example:    Students will work in cohorts, or groups of the same students, as much as possible. Cohorts will distance themselves from other groups to limit exposure to other students.  Classrooms will be configured to support physical distancing. Schools will work to reduce class sizes and when necessary, alternate space such as multi-purpose rooms will be used as classrooms.  Lunch and recess breaks will be staggered, as well as drop-off and pick-up times.  Protocols will be in place to safely move students through the school and reduce congestion in hallways and common areas.  Students and staff will be required to stay home when they are unwell and there will be screening protocols for all people entering a school.  Students will be educated on the importance of physical distancing and hand washing.  Enhanced cleaning protocols will be followed in the school and on the school bus.  To reduce the number of students on buses, parents will be asked to transport their children to and from school whenever possible and buses will be added where necessary.  The plan for September is based on current evidence and recommendations of the Chief Public Health Office. While in-school learning is the preferred model, back-up plans will be in place to move to at-home learning should public health conditions change.  Staff will return to school on September 1 and students on September 8. Orientation on new operational requirements will be held for all staff. Professional learning for teachers will focus on the revised curriculum, online teaching and learning, and student wellness.    https://archive.vn/wip/ajiDY    https://archive.vn/wip/EytX5

column15: When schools K-12 return on 8 September, some levels will be required to wear facemasks.   UPEI remains in online mode with the exception of Veterinary and Nursing Faculty.     https://archive.vn/BYm2J    Updates to the mask policy include:    masks will be required for all students K-12 while riding the bus;  masks will be required for bus drivers when they are not seated, facing forward and driving the bus;  masks will be required for students in Grades 7-12 during transitions and emergency procedures;  masks will be required for staff teaching Grades 7-12 during transitions and emergency procedures;   masks will be required for any visitor to the school during transitions and emergency procedures; and   exceptions will be made on a case-by-case basis.  These changes were made in consultation with the Public Schools Branch, Commission scolaire de langue français, the Prince Edward Island Teachers’ Federation, Canadian Union of Public Sector Employees and the Prince Edward Island Home and School Federation along with Prince Edward Island’s Chief Public Health Office.     Mask policies for students and staff in grades K-6 while in school have not changed. Masks are encouraged when physical distancing cannot be maintained.     Schools and buses will have masks available for any student or staff member who needs one.     In September, students, families and staff can expect to see the following in schools:    physical distancing, directional signage and increased hand washing and sanitizing stations;  staggered recess, lunch and arrival and departure times;  classrooms reorganized to increase spacing;  movement and schedules in cohorts to minimize contact;  cohorts will be kept as small as possible;  a focus on student and staff well-being;  revised curriculum to address potential gaps;  breakfast, snack and lunch programs will continue under CPHO food premises guidelines;   students will have the opportunity to engage in all subject areas, although some subject areas may look different;   school sports will be paused during school start-up; and  student committees such as Student Council activities will need to follow all guidelines and virtual options will be encouraged.   Additionally, schools have the option to stagger start dates and hold an orientation day for new grades to the school on Tuesday, September 8th. If a school chooses to do this, the remaining grades would start school on Wednesday, September 9th. Schools will communicate directly to their school community with their intended start dates.     https://archive.vn/dVFWn

column69: Self-isolation remains required for anyone arriving on the Island from outside of the Atlantic Bubble.   Islanders who are rotational workers (those who travel frequently or routinely outside the Atlantic Bubble (within Canada), spending at least half of their time working outside of Atlantic Canada), do not need to self-isolate or work-isolate. Instead, rotational workers must be tested on a regular basis, monitor for symptoms and follow public health measures such as physical distancing, frequent hand washing and wearing a non-medical mask when physical distancing is not possible. This protocol has been in place since the early onset of the pandemic to balance an acceptable risk of transmission with the need for rotational workers to see their families for the limited time they are home.    Effective October 1, individuals who work outside of the Atlantic Bubble (within Canada) who are required to work outside of their home upon return to PEI can apply to work-isolate, via a self-declaration form that will be available on the provincial website. A letter from the worker’s employer indicating their schedule is required. More information on the work-isolate declaration will be available online early next week.     https://archive.vn/zr1Wg

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

Canada Emergency Response Benefits ended on 26 September.    Other support still in place- detailed here:    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155358/https://www.canada.ca/en/services/benefits/covid19-emergency-benefits.html    This article  suggests that after the CERB ends, eligibility for receiving other kinds of support will be widened, so I have left this coding as a 2F ("The government has announced the implementation of certain measures to make it easier to access EI benefits for workers who, until now, have been eligible to receive the CERB. Some of these measures incorporate the bulk of legislative changes brought to the Employment Insurance Act (Emergency Response Benefit) under Interim Order No. 7") and (The federal government plans on introducing three new income support benefits to replace the CERB for workers not eligible for EI.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155613/https://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/en/knowledge/publications/8df5a679/what-to-expect-after-the-canada-emergency-response-benefit-comes-to-an-end

column86: From 1 October, PEI will adapt a 3 tiered colour coded system: Beginning Thursday, the province will be in the green phase or New Normal phase. Other phases include Caution (yellow) and Restricted (red). Key factors such as transmission of COVID-19 in the province, public health capacity (to carry out testing, operation isolation and contact tracing), health care system capacity, outbreak risk in vulnerable settings such as long-term care, risk of importation of COVID-19 into the province, and overall impact to Islanders will be used to determine when to move between the various alert levels.     https://archive.vn/KskIO

column103: As of 20 November, non-medical masks or face coverings will be mandatory in all indoor public spaces in PEI.   Masks will be mandatory in locations, including but not limited to:    Stores and retail businesses;  Personal services and salons;  Restaurants (except when eating or drinking);  Arts, sports and recreation facilities (except during exercise or when masks cannot be worn);  Places of worship;  Government buildings where public services are provided;  Taxis and public transit; and  Workplaces that are open to the public.  Exemptions to mandatory masks include, but not limited to:    Children under the age of 2;  Children under 5 who will not wear a mask;  Anyone who cannot remove a mask without assistance; and  Valid medical reasons, such as active breathing problems (most people with underlying medical conditions can wear a mask safely).    https://archive.vn/wip/jYQhy

column69: Effective today (24 Nov) PEI has suspended participation in the Atlantic Bubble for two weeks, and are advising Islander not to travel outside of PEI for anything other than essential trips and work, and that they need to apply for pre-travel approval.     https://archive.vn/Tz9kD
column115: From 24 Nov, LTCF Residents must now choose a list of six visitors only, and only two may visit at a time. Those visits will once again have to be held in a designated area and may have to once again be scheduled. Physical distancing between the resident and visitor must be maintained. The length of the visit will be at the home's discretion, the guidelines say.     With PEI leaving the travel bubble, partners in care (family and friends of someone in LTCFs) can only go to visit their loved ones in Long term care facilities after they have completed 14 days of isolation if they have been off of the island, and have no symptoms of COVID.      https://archive.vn/Tz9kD    https://archive.vn/t4E6Q
column117: With PEI leaving the travel bubble, partners in care (family and friends of someone in LTCFs) can only go to visit their loved ones in Long term care facilities after they have completed 14 days of isolation if they have been off of the island, and have no symptoms of COVID.      https://archive.vn/Tz9kD

column88: Islander who require COVID-19 tests can now book their appointment online, and received a scheduled appt in either Summerside or Charlottetown, reducing waits at the drop in COVID testing sites and clinics.     https://archive.vn/UeMRG

column103: Face masks are now available for low-income families at all Food Bank locations across the Island.     https://archive.vn/wip/RxE9J

column81: on Dec 3 it was announced that the PEI Govt has created a COVID-19 Local Advertising Fund to provide a max contribution of $2500 to PEI businesses to offset the cost of advertising their consumer goods or services to the local PEI market during the peak holiday shopping season.     https://archive.vn/YeP5S

column60: People are still requested to stay home if they feel ill.     https://archive.vn/eEupx
column69: The Premier announced today that participation in the Atlantic Bubble (which would not require quarantine) is suspended for an additional 2 weeks until the 21 December.     https://archive.vn/eEupx
column88: Testing remains open to anyone symptomatic.     https://archive.vn/eEupx
column90: All contact tracing efforts continue to be extensive and comprehensive in the province.     https://archive.vn/eEupx

column15: From Today, 7 December, high schools in the Capital Region (Charlottetown) have moved to remote learning. School affected: Colonel Grey, Charlottetown Rural, Bluefield High School and Grades 10-12 at Ecole Francois Buote.     https://archive.vn/n89Qj
column24: In-room dining at Restaurants has been suspended for 2 weeks from 7-21 December. Take out and delivery can continue.   Gyms, fitness facilities, museums, libraries, bingo halls and casinos will be closed.   Personal services can remain open for appointment only. Retails stores must operate at 50% capacity.   Daycares can continue to operate.     https://archive.vn/4g3GW    Working from home is encouraged where possible.   https://archive.vn/w7jZO
column33: Events are cancelled for the 2 week circuit breaker mini 'lockdown' from 7-21 December.     https://archive.vn/4g3GW
column42: Organised gatherings (faith) are limited to 10 people indoors or outdoors.   During a 2 week circuit breaker, all personal gatherings are prohibited.   A household can only associate with two persons outside of their household.     https://archive.vn/4g3GW
column60: Island residents are requested to stay at home unless shopping for essentials (groceries, pharmacy and bank). Households should designate ONE person to do essential shopping.     https://archive.vn/4g3GW
column69: Travel outside of the province must be requested and approved, and all entries to the island are required to self isolate for 14 days upon arrival. Fines will be issued.     https://archive.vn/4g3GW
column115: From 7 December, there will be no external visitors to either hospitals or long term care facilities. Only 'partners in care', those who are designated as part of a LTCF resident's care team are allowed to attend the facilities, and only one may be designated to do so.     https://archive.vn/avgh0

column106: PEI will begin the vaccination of long term care workers and health workers on PEI with the Pfizer vaccine today. Free of charge.     https://archive.vn/wip/yFCaS

column24: Restaurants and licensed premises can re-open in-room dining with a closing time of 11:00pm and a max table size of 10 people. A limit of 50 people per premise, with the option for an additional 50 people with operational plan approved.     Retail stores, markets and craft fairs may operate at 50% capacity    Gyms, fitness centres, museums and libraries may operate at 50% capacity     personal services may operate on an appointment only basis. Masks are required by both staff and patron.     https://archive.vn/LVufx
column33: Organised gatherings and events such as concerts, worship services and movie theatres can operate with up to 50 people. A second group of 50 people is permitted with an approved operational plan. Weddings and funerals can include up to 50 people, plus officiants. Weddings and funerals are NOT eligible for a second group of 50 people.     https://archive.vn/LVufx
column42: Personal gatherings (indoor and outdoor) are permitted with up to 10 additional people outside of your household. These 10 people should be as consistent as possibly and physical distancing should be maintained as much as possible.     https://archive.vn/LVufx
column60: As previously, Islanders are encouraged to stay at home if they feel unwell.     https://archive.vn/LVufx
column69: 14 day quarantine upon arrival from any other province is still required.     https://archive.vn/LVufx
column115: Visiting restrictions for long term care facilities have been eased effective immediately to allow for 2 partners in care and 6 designated visitors to support care. A maximum of 2 visitors may visit a resident at one time. Visits must be scheduled, and cannot occur in the residents' rooms.     https://archive.vn/CEftP

column74: In addition to the Canadian border generally being closed to non-essential travel, or to those without permission to enter Canada, Canada has banned all travel from the UK as of the 20th December due to the new variant of COVID. This ban originally set for 72 hrs, was then extended to 6th Jan 2021.     https://archive.vn/OGmTZ

column79: Property tax deferral due dates have now passed and were due on 31 December, 2020    https://archive.vn/wip/5CW3Q

column86: On January 20, 2020, Canada’s Chief Public Health Officer (Dr. Theresa Tam) and Deputy Chief Public  Health Officer (Dr. Howard Njoo) held their first media briefing on the novel coronavirus    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203170514/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/news/2020/01/government-of-canada-officials-to-hold-a-media-availability-on-a-novel-coronavirus.html

column88: The first specialized COVID-19 clinic opened in Montreal's former Hotel-Dieu hospital. The clinic offers various services, including patient evaluation and testing. The clinic is accessible by appointment only. If a medical consultation in a specialized COVID-19 clinic is required, the Info-Santé nurse will book an appointment for you.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201126165319/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/coronavirus-covid-19-quebec-1.5490706

column15: Collège International Marie de France, a Montreal school, is suspending some classes because a student was being tested for COVID-19. It suspended all secondary school classes, and all of the other class levels remained active and hygiene measures were taken. If the student tests negative for COVID-19, classes would resume, but if the test comes back positive, the college would remain shut for 14 days.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129031648/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-montreal-school-suspends-classes-because-a-student-is-being-tested-1.4847760
column74: Staff at the Sainte-Justine children's hospital in Montreal have been asked to curtail their travel and not report to work if they have visited certain countries in hopes of limiting the risk of spreading COVID-19. The list of countries drawn up by the Sainte-Justine - mainland China, Hong Kong, South Korea, Iran, India, Egypt, Japan, Singapore, northern Italy, France as well as Seattle, USA - is much longer than that of the federal government, which advises Canadians to limit travel to China, Iran and northern Italy.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129031428/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-sainte-justine-children-s-hospital-in-montreal-asks-workers-to-limit-travel-stay-home-1.4846465

column24: Due to the high number of workers that make up the Saint-Laurent business community and the economic weight it represents for Québec as a whole, the Mayor of Saint-Laurent urged companies on the territory to launch their back-up business continuity plans to ensure that operations continue to run smoothly. Additional prevention measures are expected for all businesses and restaurants in Saint-Laurent.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129144117/http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=5977%2C43117560&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&id=32463&ret=http%3A%2F%2Fville.montreal.qc.ca%2Fpls%2Fportal%2Furl%2Fpage%2Fprt_vdm_en%2Frep_annonces_ville%2Frep_communiques%2Fcommuniques
column33: Several public events were cancelled in Montreal, such as the World's Figure Skating Championships (scheduled to run March 18-22) or Saint-Laurent's Urban Sugar Shack (March 21).    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129140716/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-the-world-figure-skating-championships-in-montreal-have-been-cancelled-1.4848246  https://web.archive.org/web/20201129141831/http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=5977%2C43117560&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&id=32475&ret=http%3A%2F%2Fville.montreal.qc.ca%2Fpls%2Fportal%2Furl%2Fpage%2Fprt_vdm_en%2Frep_annonces_ville%2Frep_communiques%2Fcommuniques
column74: Premier Francois Legault said his government was preparing to issue a directive to hospital staff ordering them to give up travelling abroad, whether for professional or personal reasons. He also recommended that students who have returned from a school trip to a country at risk be forced to quarantine themselves for two weeks, whether or not they have symptoms.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129145449/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-quebec-premier-asks-province-s-health-workers-to-halt-all-travel-1.4848644
column86: In Montreal, the Borough of Saint-Laurent has announced the introduction of special prevention measures to keep the virus from spreading among employees and visitors at all municipal buildings that are accessible to the public. Since each person can help to effectively limit the spread of the virus by using basic hygiene techniques and good habits, reminder posters have been installed in common spaces and washrooms.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201129144117/http://ville.montreal.qc.ca/portal/page?_pageid=5977%2C43117560&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL&id=32463&ret=http%3A%2F%2Fville.montreal.qc.ca%2Fpls%2Fportal%2Furl%2Fpage%2Fprt_vdm_en%2Frep_annonces_ville%2Frep_communiques%2Fcommuniques

column115: With the province in emergency state, regular visits to private and public long-term care centers were banned throughout Quebec. Moreover, people aged 70 years and more were recommended to stay home and limit their movements to avoid exposing themselves to coronavirus except in exceptional cases such as medical appointments.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201130045917/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-declare-l-etat-d-urgence-sanitaire-interdit-les-visites-dans-les-centres-h/

column24: The following workplaces were required to close until March 30th:  - Cultural sector: libraries, museums, theaters, bars, clubs, etc.  - Entertainment sector: spas/swimming pools/saunas, ski stations, arcades and movie theaters, gyms, zoos, aquariums, etc.    For restaurants, only 50% of clients are allowed to dine in. All-you-can-eat buffets have to close.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200927225300/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-exige-la-fermeture-de-plusieurs-commerces-endroits-publics-et-lieux-de-ras/
column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.
column115: Measures to protect elderly people are announced again by Francois Legault : regular visits to private and public long-term care centers were banned throughout Quebec. People aged 70 years and more were recommended to stay home except for going out for groceries and medical appointments.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200927225300/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-exige-la-fermeture-de-plusieurs-commerces-endroits-publics-et-lieux-de-ras/

column15: All schools, universities, and CEGEP in Quebec will be closed for two weeks.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201117174635/https://cdn-contenu.quebec.ca/cdn-contenu/adm/min/sante-services-sociaux/publications-adm/lois-reglements/decret-177-2020.pdf?1584224223
column24: The following workplaces were added to the list of closure :  - outdoor centers  - all religious gathering (except for essential gatherings such as funerals)    Employers are strongly encouraged to let their employees work from home.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130050611/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-mobilise-plus-que-jamais-assure-francois-legault/
column60: The Quebec Premier asked Quebec residents to limit their movements, keep social distance from one another and avoid taking part in any non-essential gatherings.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130050611/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-mobilise-plus-que-jamais-assure-francois-legault/
column74: Following the announcements from the Prime Minister Justin Trudeau, Quebec is in favor of closing the borders to non-Canadian residents, except for the US citizens.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130050611/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-mobilise-plus-que-jamais-assure-francois-legault/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201202205854/https://globalnews.ca/news/6685905/coronavirus-airports-screening-complaints/

column79: To simplify the lives of individuals and businesses affected by the exceptional situation stemming from COVID-19, the government has asked Revenu Québec to apply flexibility measures for individuals and businesses in Quebec during income tax filing season.  - The deadline for producing and filing income tax return is postponed to June 1.  - For individuals and individuals in business, the deadline for applying balances due related to income tax returns for the 2019 taxation year is postponed to July 31, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200327134547/http://www.finances.gouv.qc.ca/documents/Communiques/en/COMEN_20200317.pdf

To harmonise its practices with those of the Canada Revenue Agency, the Quebec government announced that for individuals and individuals in business, the deadline for applying balances due related to income tax returns for the 2019 taxation year is postponed to September 1st, 2020 (instead of July 31st as announced previously on March 17th).    https://web.archive.org/web/20200608142406/http://www.finances.gouv.qc.ca/documents/Communiques/en/COMEN_20200318.pdf
column103: The province’s top public health official asked Quebec residents to avoid using masks for preventive purposes. He announced face masks need to be reserved for health care workers and patients with the virus.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201202230506/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-quebec-officials-urge-people-to-stop-wearing-masks-to-prevent-shortage-1.4858110

column69: The Premier of Quebec strongly encouraged Quebec residents to avoid non-essential travels from one region to another.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201202233232/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-premier-ministre-francois-legault-donne-de-nouvelles-consignes-pour-freiner-la-propagation-du-cor/
column77: A new temporary program was set up to financially support workers who are not eligible for other income replacement programs and who are affected by containment measures.  The government is offering up to $573 a week for those in self-isolation who are unable to work. Workers can receive the weekly stipend for up to one month. A form is available as of Thursday, March 19th, on the Quebec government’s website and the government promised a two-day processing period to ensure quick financial assistance.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201202235203/https://globalnews.ca/news/6682191/quebec-coronavirus-march16/
column79: Québec followed suit with the federal government concerning its measure to reduce by 25% in 2020 the amount of mandatory withdrawal from a registered retirement income fund (RRIF). This measure will protect retirees who possess RRIFs who are put at a disadvantage by the state of stock markets.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200918065626/http://www.finances.gouv.qc.ca/documents/Communiques/en/COMEN_20200319.pdf
column81: Quebec Premier François Legault announced Thursday a $2.5-billion (CAD) aid package to help businesses weather the current economic crisis caused by the pandemic. The $2.5 billion will be used to help businesses experiencing liquidity problems connected to coronavirus. Businesses applying for assistance will not only have to show a causal link to the coronavirus pandemic but also show profitability after. The government will be offering loans and loan guarantees of a minimum of $50,000 and very advantageous rates. (currency: December 2nd, 2020)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201202234316/https://globalnews.ca/news/6700978/quebec-coronavirus-march19/
column115: Quebec Premier reminded those who are 70 years old and older to avoid gathering in restaurants and shops or organizing dinner events, and encouraged them again to stay home as much as possible. He also asked the young people to call their grandparents to remind them of all protection measures.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201202233232/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-premier-ministre-francois-legault-donne-de-nouvelles-consignes-pour-freiner-la-propagation-du-cor/

column79: Due to COVID-19, the government is postponed student loan debt repayment (no payments to make during the next six months). The measure automatically applies to all Aide financière aux études clients, including those whose accounts are in collection.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203034007/https://www.quebec.ca/en/education/student-financial-assistance/repayment/deferred-payment/

column24: Starting from midnight (March 22nd-23rd) until May 1st, the following workplaces are required to close:  - shopping malls (except for grocery stores, pharmacies and liquor stores)  - hair / beauty salons  - dining space in restaurants    https://web.archive.org/web/20201130054157/https://www.quebec.ca/en/premier/actualites/detail/le-premier-ministre-du-quebec-francois-legault-accentue-les-mesures-d-urgence-pour-proteger-la-popul/

Ahmed Hussen, Minister of Families, Children and Social Development, and Danielle McCann, Quebec’s Minister of Health and Social Services, announced that the governments of Canada and Quebec have reached an agreement to make additional funding of over $21.4 million (CAD) available through the Reaching Home program for 2020–2021. All Quebec regions that are already receiving Reaching Home funding will have access to additional funds.    These funds include:  $19,514,375 (CAD) allocated to the Designated Communities funding stream;  $1,902,653 (CAD) allocated to the Rural and Remote Homelessness funding stream.    Note: Nationally, the Government of Canada will set aside a portion of the $157.5 million (CAD) in funding previously announced by the Prime Minister to ensure the possibility of reinvesting in specific communities that are dealing with a larger COVID-19 outbreak. column42: Quebec is allowing indoor gatherings of up to 50 people, starting on June 22, provided social distancing rules are respected. In places with seating, and specifically where no one is talking, people will be expected to stay 1.5 metres away from one another, Dr. Arruda (province's public health director) said. That includes university classrooms and movie theatres.   In larger gathering areas where there is a lot of circulation, including in restaurants, Quebecers will still be expected to keep two metres apart. Arruda strongly recommended wearing a mask or face covering when in these large indoor gatherings.  "Just as in gatherings in private places, the physical distancing will not be applicable to those people coming from the same household," he added. When it comes to concerts, there will need to be extra space between the performer and spectator, Dr. Richard Massé, a senior public health official, explained.  When it comes to indoor gatherings at home, the maximum will still be 10 people from a maximum of three households.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201207022517/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/public-indoor-gatherings-of-up-to-50-people-allowed-in-quebec-1.5612451
column60: Quebec is allowing indoor gatherings of up to 50 people, starting on June 22, provided social distancing rules are respected.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207022517/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/public-indoor-gatherings-of-up-to-50-people-allowed-in-quebec-1.5612451

column81: The Minister of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, the Minister of Forests, Wildlife and Parks, as well as the federal Minister of Agriculture and Agri-Food, are announcing that the Government of Canada and the Government of Quebec will join forces to financially support Quebec fish farmers in the exceptional context created by COVID-19.  Quebec fish farmers are an important cog in the wheel of food production. The closure of restaurants and the cessation of fishing activities have had a major impact on Quebec's fish farming industry. This situation has led to a drop in the volume of fish purchased from fish farmers and generated a surplus of inventory. The financial contribution from the Quebec government and the federal government is in the order of $408,000 and $612,000 respectively (CAD). This financial support will therefore make it possible to minimize the fish mortalities related to these surpluses and to limit financial losses by supporting the stocking of public water bodies.  (The portion from the Quebec government was converted with a currency late as of Dec 6th.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207025254/https://www.canada.ca/en/agriculture-agri-food/news/2020/07/emergency-response-the-governments-of-canada-and-quebec-join-forces-to-help-quebec-fish-farmers.html

column103: Starting July 13, everyone aged 12 years or older must wear a mask or facial covering in public transportation (subways, buses, taxis, etc.). This is strongly recommended for children aged 2-12 years.    https://web.archive.org/web/20200926220231/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/port-du-couvre-visage-ou-du-masque-obligatoire-dans-les-transports-en-commun-des-le-13-juillet/

column24: Quebec will allow private sector employees to head back to the office in an effort to revitalize the struggling downtown cores of the province's largest cities. Labour Minister Jean Boulet told at a news conference that businesses can bring back up to a quarter of their employees to the office starting Saturday (July 18). The province is strongly recommending, however, people continue working remotely if possible.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207030531/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/quebec-says-private-sector-offices-can-reopen-at-one-quarter-capacity-on-saturday-1.5025151
column103: Starting July 18, Quebecers (12 years or older) will have to wear a mask or a facial covering in closed public spaces throughout Quebec. These include:  - retail shops / shopping malls  - grocery stores / pharmacies  - government / municipal buildings  - beauty/personal care services such as hairdressers  - religious places  - movie theaters  - all shared spaces in a building (corridors, elevators, entrance halls)  - public transportation    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207025910/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-port-du-couvre-visage-sera-obligatoire-dans-plusieurs-espaces-publics-fermes-des-le-18-juillet/

column15: All Quebec schools are to be reopen in September, following enhanced sanitation measures.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207081431/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/all-quebec-schools-to-reopen-in-september-education-minister-1.4986194

column103: Individuals who refuse to wear masks in indoor public spaces will have to pay a fine.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207045242/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-premier-ministre-francois-legault-annonce-un-resserrement-des-mesures-envers-les-recalcitrants/

column15: For the red zone schools:  - Masks are mandatory for 5th and 6th grade students.  - Masks are mandatory for all school staff.  - 2 meter social distancing is required.  - All extracurricular activities are suspended.  - For post-secondary institutions, virtual classes have to be implemented as much as possible. Labs or internships can be in-person.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052806/https://www.quebec.ca/sante/problemes-de-sante/a-z/coronavirus-2019/systeme-alertes-regionales-et-intervention-graduelle/palier-4-alerte-maximale-zone-rouge/
column24: The Greater Montreal, Riviere-du-Nord, Chaudiere-Appalaches (except for Les Etchemin, Montmagny and L'Islet) and a portion of Capitale-Nationale regions move to the "red zone". Regions in the green went on to the yellow stage, and yellow regions to the orange stage.    In the red zone, temporary measures are put in place:  - private gatherings are banned.  - indoors activities are banned, and outdoor activities should respect 2 meter social distancing.  - indoor spaces such as movie theatres, museums are closed.  - exceptions are allowed for religion or for funerals but a maximum number of 25 is accepted.  - bars, casinos and restaurants have to close down (except for take-outs and deliveries).  - retail stores remain open with social distancing measures.  - personal beauty services remain open.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207045358/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/certaines-regions-passent-au-palier-dalerte-maximale/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201207050228/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-met-tout-en-oeuvre-pour-casser-la-deuxieme-vague/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052806/https://www.quebec.ca/sante/problemes-de-sante/a-z/coronavirus-2019/systeme-alertes-regionales-et-intervention-graduelle/palier-4-alerte-maximale-zone-rouge/
column42: For the red zone residents, all indoor and outdoor gatherings are banned.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052806/https://www.quebec.ca/sante/problemes-de-sante/a-z/coronavirus-2019/systeme-alertes-regionales-et-intervention-graduelle/palier-4-alerte-maximale-zone-rouge/
column60: A fine of 1000$ (CAD) can be imposed for illegal private gatherings.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201207050228/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-met-tout-en-oeuvre-pour-casser-la-deuxieme-vague/
column69: Non-essential travels to a yellow, orange or green zone are highly discouraged. Operations to raise awareness of the danger of internal movement will be implemented on the roads, in collaboration with the Ministry of Transportation.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207045358/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/certaines-regions-passent-au-palier-dalerte-maximale/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201207050228/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-met-tout-en-oeuvre-pour-casser-la-deuxieme-vague/
column81: Quebec Government plans a new aid program for companies in the maximum alert zones. The first two programs (PACTE / PAUPME) that were implemented at the beginning of the pandemic remain, and now l’Aide aux Entreprises en Régions en Alerte Maximale (AERAM) will allow the businesses that were forced to shut down to pay fixed expenses without having to reimburse them. These include municipal taxes, rent, insurance, hydro, etc. This cannot exceed 80% of the loaned amount or 15000$ (CAD).    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207050907/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/une-nouvelle-aide-pour-les-entreprises-des-regions-en-alerte-maximale/
column115: In red zones, visits from caregivers and visits for a humanitarian reason are the only allowed ones. Other visits are banned - for authorized visits, maximum two people are allowed per day for a patient in a LTC facility. In green and yellow zones, limited visits are recommended.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207045358/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/certaines-regions-passent-au-palier-dalerte-maximale/

column81: The government announced an additional financial support of 50 million dollars (CAD) to support producers and broadcasters for cultural events. It will be used to reimburse tickets that could not be sold due to new restrictions, making up for maximum 75% of the unsold ticket value. Production costs will be covered as well. Around 500 cultural organizations will be able to benefit from this policy. This aid will be used until March 31, 2020.  (currency: December 6, 2020)    https://web.archive.org/save/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-legault-investit-50-m-de-plus-pour-aider-le-milieu-culturel/

column90: All Quebecers are invited to download Covid-19 alert app on their mobile phones. Developed by the federal government, this app allows people to see if anyone they have been in close contact with for more than 15 minutes was tested positive for the virus.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052234/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/les-quebecois-invites-a-telecharger-lapplication-alerte-covid-fr/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052535/https://www.quebec.ca/sante/problemes-de-sante/a-z/coronavirus-2019/alerte-covid/

column69: More regions are declared to be in the "red" zone. Measures associated with the zone will have to be put in place by October 16th. Those concerning schools and sport start on October 19th.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207052631/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-du-quebec-procede-a-une-mise-a-jour-des-paliers-dalerte/

column88: Quebec Premier insisted that only those who are symptomatic and those who have been in contact with someone tested positive for Covid-19 should get tested.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207055142/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/les-efforts-des-quebecois-fonctionnent-le-premier-ministre-francois-legault-remercie-les-quebecois-e-7/

column15: More secondary students in the red zone will have to alternate between virtual classes and in-person classes as the number of Covid-19 cases failed to decrease throughout the month of October.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207055437/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/prolongement-des-mesures-en-zones-rouges-jusquau-23-novembre/
column24: After announcing red zone measures on October 1st, the government announced additional 4 weeks of restrictions (until November 23rd) to be put in place to reduce the transmission of Covid-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207055437/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/prolongement-des-mesures-en-zones-rouges-jusquau-23-novembre/

In the red zone, restaurants, gyms, theaters, and all businesses that had to close down will have to remain closed until January 11th, 2021.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207055922/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-propose-un-contrat-moral-aux-quebecois-pour-le-temps-des-fetes/
column42: The government proposes a "moral contract" to Quebecers in order to spend the holidays with families (24-27 December) by following the steps below:  1. Keep the current situation until Christmas.  2. Do a voluntary self-isolation for a week before the holiday period and for a week after the holiday period.  3. Limit the gatherings during Christmas to maximum 10 people.  4. Protect the others, and especially the elderly.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207055922/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/le-gouvernement-propose-un-contrat-moral-aux-quebecois-pour-le-temps-des-fetes/

Finally, after re-evaluating the situation, the government announced that the regions in the red zone won't allow people to move to spend Christmas together with family at a different address. Exceptions only apply for those who live alone. For the other zones (yellow and orange), the rules announced on November 19th still apply.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201207060537/https://www.quebec.ca/premier-ministre/actualites/detail/les-rassemblements-seront-interdits-durant-la-periode-des-fetes-dans-les-zones-rouges/

C:  A resident at a long-term care home in Quebec City has become the first Quebecer to receive a novel coronavirus vaccine. The first administered dose in the province came as shipments arrived for the first part of the rollout plan in two long-term care homes. column15: To limit the spread of the novel coronavirus, schools are closing for a longer period during Christmas break. Schools will therefore close early but students will be required to take part in online learning activities from Dec. 17 to Dec. 22, 2020. Grade schools in the province will reopen at their previously scheduled dates either on Jan. 5, 6 or 7, 2021 depending on the region. High schools will continue with online classes after the break, with in-person schooling resuming on Jan 11, 2021. Specialized schools will remain open as will daycare services but only for essential workers.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201222042410/https://globalnews.ca/news/7471837/quebec-coronavirus-holiday-school-closings-announcement/
column24: Office worker telework is mandatory in all regions from December 17, 2020 to January 10, 2021, inclusively, except for workers whose physical presence is deemed by their employer to be required to maintain the ongoing activities of a public or private organization.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201221182449/https://www.quebec.ca/en/health/health-issues/a-z/2019-coronavirus/covid-19-related-instructions-holiday-season/
column42: Covid-19 related instructions for the holiday season will be applied from December 17 2020 to Jan 10, 2021.  - Indoor and outdoor private gatherings in regions and territories that are on maximum alert (red zone) will be prohibited throughout the holiday season. A person who lives alone can join another family’s bubble, but it must always be the same bubble.  - Gatherings of no more than six people will be permitted in regions and areas located in alert (orange) zones. For these regions, it is recommended to do a voluntary confinement, one week before and one week after the time of the gatherings.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201221182449/https://www.quebec.ca/en/health/health-issues/a-z/2019-coronavirus/covid-19-related-instructions-holiday-season/

column106: A,C:  In Québec, the COVID-19 vaccine will be free for anyone who wants it. People in priority groups are receiving their first round of the COVID-19 vaccine at 21 sites that have been set up across Quebec starting December 21, 2020. Vaccinations at these sites are reserved only for priority populations, like people living in long-term care homes and health-care workers. (Pfizer-BioNTech's vaccine is used. Moderna's vaccine is expected to arrive by early next year.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201222045855/https://www.quebec.ca/en/health/health-issues/a-z/2019-coronavirus/progress-of-the-covid-19-vaccination/  https://web.archive.org/web/20201222045950/https://montreal.ctvnews.ca/covid-19-vaccine-rollout-begins-today-at-21-sites-across-quebec-1.5239798  https://web.archive.org/web/20210119094910/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/quebec-vaccine-explained-1.5828321

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.

column92: Updates to the budget released by the ministry of finance include a $211 million increase for the ministry of health, and $140 million increase in the grant given to the Saskatchewan Health authority. column60: The government announces, along with their phase one plan, that "Individuals should continue working from home if they can do so effectively." column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column90: "In cases where anyone tests positive for COVID-19, a contact investigation immediately follows where public health reaches out to anyone who may be linked to a positive case and provide them with information on testing and self-isolation. Expands mandatory masking while inside to all places with popuations of 5,000 or greater. https://web.archive.org/web/20201130182641/https://www.saskatchewan.ca/government/news-and-media/2020/november/13/covid-19-additional-public-health-measures-announced

Specifies that the following is exemptions are permitted: "The following individuals while speaking during a television or other media news interview or conference"- specifies government officials and news broadcasters AND "Clergy members or religious leaders who are leading a service or ceremony while speaking from a podium, lectern, platform, stage, desk or other standing or seating area dedicated to speaking"

column33: There is no blanket ban or restrictions imposed for events. column86: From 7th March, the Yukon Chief Medical Officer for Health began updating a webpage dedicated to Covid-19 information (https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates). This page includes information on the government's Covid-19 policy and is regularly updated with advice from the Chief Medical Officer for Health.

Since 12th March, the Yukon government has released regular video updates on Facebook and YouTube.   Sources: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129150328/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/read-transcripts-facebook-live     https://archive.vn/4oLtw
column88: On 12th March, Yukon had its first live-streamed Covid-19 update. At 28:50, one  panellist  answers a question about testing, stating that a Covid-19 testing criteria has been out for several months, that the (unpublished) criteria changes at least twice weekly and that individuals began to meet that criteria and receive a test just a few weeks before.    Source: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RvdTvxFRUOk&list=PL4B1jekdBO2rkKxe2fdbQZFIocNRpWZAH&index=1

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html    Have coded as 2F because this does not seem to apply to anyone who does not file taxes- there for not 'informal' workers, so not ALL.

column90: On 22nd March, it was announced that Yukon had its first cases of Covid-19. Such indicates that a contact tracing system is in place.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201201123045if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/covid-19-confirmed-yukon

column81: On 1st April, the Government of Yukon announced the Temporary Support for Events Funding Program, which will help businesses recover specific costs where major events have had to be cancelled due to Covid-19. Source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20201022063639if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/yukon-businesses-benefit-funding-cancelled-events    https://web.archive.org/web/20201206152747if_/https://yukon.ca/en/temporary-support-cancelled-events#program-eligibility

The grant will cover staff wages and certain building expenses including rent, utilities and cleaning costs in March, April, May and June.    The Government of Yukon did not specify how much money they expected to spend on this Grant.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206154701if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/child-care-operators-receive-additional-funding
column90: In an update on 6th April, Yukon's Chief Medical Officer of Health confirmed that whenever a new Covid-19 case emerged in Yukon, the Government of Yukon would contact anyone who had close contact with the confirmed case. column103: Mask-wearing is still not recommended but wearing masks was mentioned in passing on 7th April in the Chief Medical Officer for Health's update, where they mentioned that: "Wearing a non-medical mask such as a homemade cloth mask in the community has not been proven to protect the person wearing it. However, using non-medical mask or facial covering can be an additional measure people can take to protect others around them. It also helps people to be aware of not spreading infection and remember to not touch their face. Wearing a non-medical mask when in public or other settings is not a replacement for following proven measures such as hand washing and safe spacing."    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column15: Phase 0 of Yukon's plan for lifting Covid-19 restrictions included the halting of all in-person learning in schools for the rest of the 2019-20 school year (the 2020-21 school year begins on 20th August).
