column81: The Yukon Business Relief Program was created to support Yukon businesses whose revenue has decreased by 30% by providing them a grant of up to $30,000 CAD a month to support fixed costs between 23rd March and 22nd May. This is expected to cost the Government up to $10 million CAD.    The article referenced states that the Business Relief Program, the Paid Sick Leave Program, the Temporary Support for Events Funding Program (announced on 1st April) as well as changes to the Yukon Nominee Program, all of which have been previously announced, are expected to cost up to $21.7 million CAD ($15,522,446.21 USD).     Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206155629if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/yukon-businesses-receive-relief-funding

column60: The below source, Covid-19 updates from the Chief Medical Officer of Health, does not include any requirements or requests for Yukon residents to stay at home (unless they are sick, as per the 'Six steps to staying safe' outlined).     Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column69: On 17th April, a new Border Control Measures Order came into force which limited those entering the province to Yukon residents, non-resident family members of Yukon residents, those delivering a critical or essential service, those exercising an Aboriginal or treaty right and those transiting through Yukon to a neighbouring jurisdiction (the latter are only allowed to be in Yukon for 24 hours).    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129133348/https://yukon.ca/en/news/new-border-control-measures-come-force

column90: A Government of Yukon update on 20th April stated that for all confirmed Covid-19 cases in Yukon, Yukon Communicable Disease Control will contact those who have had close contact with the confirmed case to inform them of what steps they should take (e.g. self-isolating and looking out for Covid-19 symptoms). They state that the advice given will be specific to each contacted individual and their circumstances.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201201112114if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates
column103: April 17, 2020: The Minister of Transport announced measures requiring all air passengers to have a non-medical mask or face covering to cover their mouth and nose during travel. These measures come into effect at noon EDT on April 20, 2020    https://web.archive.org/web/20201119002605/https://www.canada.ca/en/transport-canada/news/2020/04/new-measures-introduced-for-non-medical-masks-or-face-coverings-in-the-canadian-transportation-system.html    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker

column79: On 23rd April, a Ministerial Order under the Civil Emergency Measures Act was signed which extended the deadline for paying property tax from 2nd July to 2nd September for citizens and businesses.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206161219if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/property-tax-payment-deadline-extended-september-2

column88: Yukon's Chief Medical Officer for Health announced on 24th April that from 27th April, the criteria for those tested for Covid-19 would be expanded.     Those tested for Covid-19 would include those with one of the covid symptoms (fever, chills, cough, difficulty breathing, a sore throat or hoarse voice, headache, runny nose or nasal congestion, unexplained vomiting or diarrhoea, fatigue or muscle aches, or loss of smell or taste) who had travelled outside Yukon in the past 14 days or had close contact with anyone who has travelled outside Yukon.     Even if someone does not have travel history but is symptomatic with fever, cough, or difficulty breathing, they can be tested for Covid-19 as well.    There will also be greater testing in long-term care facilities and the Whitehorse Emergency Shelter.    However, deciding who is tested is ultimately at the health care providers' discretion. They are expected to use their clinical expertise to decide.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130165725if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/april-24-2020-yukons-chief-medical-officer-health-provides-update-covid-19

column81: On 4th May, it was announced that the aviation sector will receive $3.56 million CAD (2,526,974.25 USD) in support as a result of Covid-19's impact on revenues.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206161653if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/new-support-available-yukons-aviation-industry

column86: On 8th May, the Yukon Government launched a non-medical Covid-19 information line. The line is described as providing 'Yukon specific information about travel and borders, self-isolation and physical distancing, enforcement, and the various social and economic supports for businesses and families'.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20200915234339/https://yukon.ca/en/news/yukon-launches-non-medical-covid-19-information-line

column81: On 11th May, the Government of Yukon announced a new support programme to help tenants who have been affected by Covid-19 pay rent. Tenants who have lost 30% of their income because of Covid-19 and who reside in private non-subsidised market rental housing can apply for the grant to assist with paying rent between April and June. Those who apply may receive 50% of median market rent based on unit size.     The Government of Yukon did not specify how much they expect the programme will cost.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20200915234234/https://yukon.ca/en/news/new-support-will-help-tenants-pay-rent-during-covid-19

column15: For Phase 1 of Yukon's plan for lifting Covid-19 restrictions (May 15th - June 30th), schools remain closed. Daycares are allowed to open to children of workers. Summer day camps can now operate along specific guidelines, but they cannot run overnight.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117155139if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/summary-yukons-plan-lifting-covid-19-restrictions
column42: For Phase 1 of the Yukon plan for lifting Covid-19 restrictions (May 15th - June 30th), gatherings are allowed of 10 people or fewer, indoor or outdoors. Exceptions might be made for funerals and religious services following a public health assessment.      Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117155139if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/summary-yukons-plan-lifting-covid-19-restrictions

column69: As a result of shifting to Phase 1 of the Yukon Covid response, guidance on travel to rural communities has been updated. Instead of asking people to avoid non-essential travel to communities, the Chief Medical Officer of Health is now asking people to limit travel to communities.    Quarantine is still required for those travelling to Yukon.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates
column81: As classes have been suspended until the end of the academic year and children have been learning from home, the Government of Yukon announced on 19th May that to offset costs incurred as a result of students learning from home, families with children in Kindergarten to Grade 12 who have been impacted by Covid-19 may apply for a one-time $250 CAD payment for each student. It is not said how much money is expected to be spent by the Government on this, but the article does state that there are 5,610 school students in Kindergarten to Grade 12 (as of 31st March), suggesting that this scheme may cost up to $1,402,500 CAD.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206163652/https://yukon.ca/en/news/government-yukon-offering-support-families-impacted-covid-19

On 20th May, the Government of Yukon announced the extension of the Business Relief Program from 22nd May, to 23rd July. The source below states that as of 19th May, over $1.6 million CAD worth of support for businesses has been approved under this programme (note that the amount expected to be spent on the programme has already been included in a data note on 9th April). The Government of Yukon does not state how much extra the programme is expected to cost as a result of its extension.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206164526if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/government-yukon-extends-support-yukon-businesses

On 22nd May, the Government of Yukon announced the Staffing Up labour market funding programme, which will receive $750,000 CAD ($534821.18 USD) to be used to encourage Yukon employers who offer critical and essential services to create new summer jobs for graduating and postsecondary level students.    Also on 22nd May, the Government of Yukon announced a programme to provide low-paid essential workers income support of up to $4 CAD per hour to a maximum of $20 per hour for up to 16 weeks. To receive this support, the worker's base wage must be no more than $20 per hour. If eligible, workers will receive a top-up of either $4 per hour or an amount that brings their wage to $20 per hour (depending on which is less). The Government of Yukon did not say how much this programme will cost.    Sources:   https://web.archive.org/web/20201025044013if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/funding-help-yukon-employers-hire-students-critical-and-essential-services  https://web.archive.org/web/20201206165208if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/essential-workers-receive-income-support-government-yukon

column24: It was announced on May 22nd that from 27th May, personal services businesses (including hair salons, barber shops, tattoo parlours, nail salons and non-registered massage therapists) are allowed to reopen so long as they had a government-approved COVID-19 operational plan.    Restaurants, bars, and public pools remain closed at this time (though restaurants can still provide take-out and deliveries).    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

Bars and public pools remain closed.     However, restaurants (which were previously only allowed to operate take-out and deliveries) can reopen on 29th May, so long as they have a government-approved Covid-19 operational plan too protect staff and customers. The Government update on 12th June (also in the source referenced below) indicates that when restaurants reopened for business on 29th May, they could only operate at 50% of capacity.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column81: On 2nd June, the Government of Yukon announced that Disability Services families would receive extra funding of $250 to $400 per month from June until August to help support them during the pandemic because of the fewer services available to them in the community.     The Government of Yukon does not state how much this will cost. However, the  source referenced below states that there are 221 families using Disability Services and 22 Approved Home Caregivers. With an extra $400 a month being offered to the former and an extra $250 a month being offered to the latter, the programme can be expected to cost a maximum of $93,900 CAD ($69,464.79 USD).    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206174321if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/disability-services-families-receive-additional-support

column103: June 3    Today, the Minister of Transport, the Honourable Marc Garneau, announced he is expanding the requirements for the use of face coverings by workers and others involved in the transportation system, to reduce the risk of COVID-19.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201118161447/https://www.canada.ca/en/transport-canada/news/2020/06/minister-garneau-announces-new-measures-for-the-use-of-face-coverings-in-the-canadian-transportation-sector.html

column81: On 4th June, the Government of Yukon announced supports for restaurants and other businesses with a liquor license, who will receive a 25% discount off of the retail price for liquor, applicable only for the time that restaurants can open at 50% capacity only (starting from 29th May). These licensees will also be refunded 50% of this year’s licence fee as they've had to close for a period during Yukon's Covid-19 response. The Government of Yukon does not state how much these supports are expected to cost them.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206175653if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/support-restaurants-announced

column88: The following document (published on March 23rd but updated on June 6th) is the Yukon Government's guidance to Whitehorse on Covid-19 testing criteria, explaining it in depth.     It explains that those tested should have any of the following symptoms (if returned from travel outside Yukon within the last 14 days, or had close contact with someone within the last 14 days who has): fever and/or chills, cough, difficulty breathing, sore throat or hoarse voice, headache, unexplained runny nose or nasal congestion, unexplained gastrointestinal symptoms (e.g. vomiting or diarrhoea), fatigue/muscle aches, loss of sense of taste and/or smell.    Those who have not travelled outside Yukon in the last 14 days (or had close contact in the last 14 days with someone who has, but has a fever and/or chills, a cough, or difficulty breathing can also be tested.    Finally, anyone hospitalised with lower respiratory illness can receive a Covid-19 test.    Sources:   https://web.archive.org/web/20200906165212/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/covid-19_testing_recommendations_2020-06-05-_whitehorse_final.pdf

column33: The policy remains that no more than 10 people can attend a single gathering.     However, from 7th June, an exception is made for faith-based services.  From this date, places of worship will be allowed to open, with social distancing measures in place. These may involve operating at 1/3rd of capacity, up to a maximum of 50 people. Sanitation measures must also be in place, so cleaning and disinfection of common, high-touch areas should be more frequent. An operational plan needs to be in place.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column74: June 8, 2020: The Canada Border Services Agency announced that as of June 8, 2020 23:59 EDT, foreign nationals who are immediate family members of Canadian citizens and permanent residents, and who do not have COVID-19 or exhibit any signs or symptoms of COVID-19, or who do not have any reason to believe they have COVID-19, will be exempt from the prohibition on entry to Canada if entering to be with an immediate family member for a period of at least 15 days    See this as essentially still a full border closure as no commercial flights operating unless in these specific circumstances for individuals who are family members.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.mccarthy.ca/en/insights/articles/covid-19-emergency-measures-tracker    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203160259/https://www.canada.ca/en/border-services-agency/news/2020/06/changes-to-travel-restrictions-for-immediate-family-members-of-canadian-citizens-and-permanent-residents.html

column24: On 11th June, the Government of Yukon announced the reopening of recycling services, which had been closed since 30th March. Free stores however, remain closed.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206180620if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/recycling-services-resume-across-yukon
column79: On 11th June, a Ministerial Order was signed that protected tenants who either has to follow a Covid-19 health-protection measure after 25th June, or  who owe back rent as a result of losing income due to Covid-19 between 26th March and 25th June. The Order prevents a landlord from evicting a tenant who has breached the tenancy agreement or the Residential Landlord and Tenant Act as a result of the tenant following a health-protection order.    The Order also allows tenants who have rent arrears as a result of them following  a health-protection order after 25th June, to pay before December 31st. If a tenant owes rent from 26th March to 25th June as a result of them, or a household member following a health-protection measure, or due to loss of income as a result of Covid-19, they must also pay the rent owed before 31st December.    Source: https://archive.vn/jPatg    http://web.archive.org/web/20201206182335/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/economic-and-social-supports-covid-19/paying-rent-loans-or

column115: From 12th June, outdoor visits for long-term care residents are now allowed. Residents can identify one visitor with whom they can visit in a pre-set outdoor location.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column51: An update on 18th June confirms that bus capacity for Whitehorse's transit system (the only inner-city bus system in Yukon) remains limited to 12 passengers.     Source:   https://web.archive.org/web/20201120114631/https://www.whitehorse.ca/Home/Components/News/News/4531/31
column81: On 18th June, the Government of Yukon announced $1,633,365 CAD ($1,201,545.87 USD) of funding for territorial sport organisations, special recreation groups, athletes and officials.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206181232if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/government-yukon-provides-more-16-million-funding-territorial-sport-and-recreation
column86: From as early as 18th June, the Government of Yukon created a website with extensive information on Covid-19. This includes information on borders and travel, childcare and education, economic and social supports, operating guidelines for industry and events, critical and essential services, general Covid-19 restrictions updates and information on health and Covid-19 (symptoms, steps to take to stay safe, etc.)    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20200618084410if_/https://yukon.ca/en/covid-19-information

column24: Announced on 12th June by the Government of Yukon, as of 19th June, bars can reopen at 50% capacity, provided they have an operational plan, approved by the Health Emergency Operations Centre.  Live music is prohibited and recreation activities including dart boards, pool tables, dance floors and gaming (such as pinball and video games) cannot be used.    However, public pools are still required to close.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column15: Phase 2 of the Yukon plan for lifting Covid-19 restrictions (from 1st July - 31st July) allowed for the resumption of in-person K-12 education for the 2020-2021 school year. However, this school year does not start until 20th August and the 2019-20 year ended in roughly mid-June. So in Phase 2, public schools remained closed in Yukon.    Sources:   http://web.archive.org/web/20201117155139if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/summary-yukons-plan-lifting-covid-19-restrictions    http://web.archive.org/web/20200801060531/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/edu/edu-school-calendar-important-dates-2019-2020.pdf
column24: On 1st July, restaurants can now operate at 100% capacity (they could previously only operate at 50% capacity). This announcement was made on 17th June.    On 24th June, the Government of Yukon announced that from 1st July, public pools can reopen so long as they have secured an approved Operational Plan and have subsequently been inspected.    With the reopening of public pools, there are no more requirements for businesses of any sector to close. However, there remain restrictions on businesses. The businesses previously required to close need to submit an operational plan to be approved in order for them to open. All other businesses, service providers and employers are required to have implemented a COVID-19 operational plan, and though it does not need to be submitted for approval, these businesses should be prepared to provide it for inspection by the government if requested.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201117170903if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates
column42: From 1st July, the maximum number of people attending an outdoors gathering increased to 50 people.  Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201114230207/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/cs/cs-cema-ministerial-authorization-outdoor-gatherings-up-to-50-people-june-18-2020.pdf
column69: The Government of Yukon announced on 24th June that from 1st July, British Columbia and Yukon residents will be allowed to travel between the two states without having to undergo 14 days self-isolation.    It was also announced that from 1st July, Northwest Territories and Nunavut residents will be able to enter Yukon without having to undergo 14 days self-isolation, but only if they travel directly to Yukon from Northwest Territories or Nunavut or via British Columbia.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates
column103: As of 1st July, (non-medical) masks must be worn in all Yukon airports. These masks should follow guidelines including: fitting securely with ties/ear loops; being changed asap if damp or dirty; being comfortable and not requiring frequent adjustment; being made of at least two layers of tightly woven material; fully covering the nose and mouth without leaving gaps.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201120235009if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/non-medical-masks-now-required-all-yukon-airports

column81: On 10th July, the Government of Yukon announced that its Rent Assist programme would be extended. The source referenced below states the programme's budget is $1.29 million CAD ($949,061.79 USD). Please note that whilst the programme has been previously mentioned in a data note on 11th May, at the time, the Government did not state how much it would cost, so the full cost of the programme has been included here.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206183921if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/support-program-help-yukoners-pay-rent-extended

column88: On 15th July, the Government of Yukon announced an expansion of its testing criteria to include those with no recent travel history outside of Yukon but whose symptoms are among those in the following list: fever, chills, cough, shortness of breath, runny nose, sore throat, loss of sense of taste or smell, headache, fatigue, loss of appetite, nausea and vomiting, diarrhoea and muscle aches.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206185432if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/expanded-testing-criteria-covid-19

column90: A Government of Yukon update on 22nd July confirmed that contact tracing is underway and anyone named as a contact of a confirmed Covid-19 case will be contacted by Yukon Communicable Disease Control.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201201112114if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column15: Schools remain closed (for the summer break), but it had been announced in July's Phase 2 of the Yukon plan for lifting of Covid-19 restrictions that schools would reopen for the 2020-21 school year (starting on 20th August). This policy remains unchanged.    Sources:  http://web.archive.org/web/20201117155139if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/summary-yukons-plan-lifting-covid-19-restrictions    http://web.archive.org/web/20200801060531/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/edu/edu-school-calendar-important-dates-2019-2020.pdf    http://web.archive.org/web/20201117154845/https://yukon.ca/en/school-holiday-dates
column33: As of 1st August, 50 people can attend an "organised, seated events occurring in a rental or public facility or venue" indoors, and 100 people can attend this outdoors.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201114230851/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/cs/cs-cema-ministerial-authorization-gatherings-up-to-100_people-aug-4-2020.pdf

column81: On 5th August, the Government of Yukon announced that support for restaurants would be extended until 1st November. Businesses with a liquor licence will continue to receive a 25% discount on the retail price of liquor.    Source:  https://web.archive.org/web/20201206190517if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/support-restaurants-extended

column103: On 12th August, the Chief Medical Officer for Health recommended to the Department of  Education that children over ten wear (non-medical) masks where social distancing cannot be  maintained (e.g. on school buses). They also emphasised that while masks are not compulsory everywhere in the community, they are recommended for situations where people cannot socially distance from  those outside their household bubble.    Source:  http://web.archive.org/web/20201130131251/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/eco/eco-live-update-transcript-august-12-2020.pdf

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

column115: From 19th August, long-term care home residents in Yukon can now receive two designated visitors indoors. This is in addition to two designated visitors outdoors.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201129124348if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column15: Last updated August 12th, a 'School during COVID-19 guideline' was published to the Government of Yukon website. It states that for the 2020-21 school year (beginning on 20th August), Kindergarten to Grade 12 students will return to classes in public schools, with sanitary measures in place. Whitehorse Grade 10-12 students will return to half-day in-class lessons, and half-day learning away  from school.    Sources:    http://web.archive.org/web/20201117152931if_/https://yukon.ca/en/school-during-covid-19-guideline    http://web.archive.org/web/20200912223955/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/edu/edu-school-during-covid-19.pdf    http://web.archive.org/web/20201117154444/https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/yukon-back-to-school-2020-1.5692673    http://web.archive.org/web/20201117154845/https://yukon.ca/en/school-holiday-dates

column51: No update on public transport restrictions on the Whitehorse Covid response news page. The Article referenced below indicates that the capacity limit of 12 people remains. It also states that the "Chief Medical Officer of Health recently approved plans to increase capacity" however no evidence of this has been found as of yet.    Sources: https://web.archive.org/web/20201120112503/https://www.whitehorse.ca/residents/covid-19    https://web.archive.org/web/20201120122042/https://www.yukon-news.com/news/families-face-challenges-in-getting-students-to-and-from-school/

column81: On 24th August, the Government of Yukon announced that they would invest $2,438,750 million CAD ($1,844,857.72 USD) in three infrastructure projects to support communities and the economy. The projects they are investing in are intended to create jobs and improve Yukoners' quality of life.     These projects are:   1. Building the Tr’ondëk Hwëch’in Youth Centre in Dawson.  2. Upgrading and expanding the sewage lagoon in Carcross to provide cleaner water. A new lift station will also be constructed in Carcross.   3. The administrative building in Watson Lake will be fit with upgrades to improve energy efficiency. On 23rd September, the Government of Yukon announced that funding for the fall intake of the Advanced Artist Award program increased by $75,000 CAD ($56,092.43 USD) to a total of $150,000 CAD.     Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201206234035if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/funding-advanced-artist-award-doubled

column77: The Canada Emergency Response Benefit (CERB) provided financial support to employed and self-employed Canadians who were directly affected by COVID-19.    Eligible were those who met these criteria:    Your work hours were reduced because of COVID-19 (see last checkbox below for more details)  You stopped working because of COVID 19  You were unable to work because of COVID-19, for example because you were taking care of someone  You were paid EI regular or fishing benefits for at least one week of benefits since December 29, 2019 and you used up your entitlement to those benefits    Applicants received $2,000 for a 4-week period (the same as $500 a week), between March 15 and September 26, 2020.    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216154619/https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/benefits/apply-for-cerb-with-cra.html

Canada Emergency Response Benefits ended on 26 September.    Other support still in place- detailed here:    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155358/https://www.canada.ca/en/services/benefits/covid19-emergency-benefits.html    This article  suggests that after the CERB ends, eligibility for receiving other kinds of support will be widened, so I have left this coding as a 2F ("The government has announced the implementation of certain measures to make it easier to access EI benefits for workers who, until now, have been eligible to receive the CERB. Some of these measures incorporate the bulk of legislative changes brought to the Employment Insurance Act (Emergency Response Benefit) under Interim Order No. 7") and (The federal government plans on introducing three new income support benefits to replace the CERB for workers not eligible for EI.)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201216155613/https://www.nortonrosefulbright.com/en/knowledge/publications/8df5a679/what-to-expect-after-the-canada-emergency-response-benefit-comes-to-an-end

column90: A Government of Yukon update on 30th September confirmed that as soon as Yukon Communicable Disease Control learns of a positive Covid-19 test they initiative contact tracing, speaking with the individual, their family and close contacts to establish their risk of having caught Covid-19. column81: On 19th October, the Government of Yukon announced a new funding package for the tourism sector, the Tourism Accommodation Sector Supplement, given the serious effects Covid-19 has had on the sector. It will cost up to $2.88 million CAD ($2,189,357.27 USD) and will be part of the Yukon Business Relief Program.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201101004832if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/new-funding-package-announced-tourism-industry-hard-hit-covid-19

On 1st April (as recorded in a previous note), the Government of Yukon announced the Temporary Support for Events Funding Program, to help businesses recover specific costs where major events have had to be cancelled due to Covid-19 . The costs of this were not specified at the time. However in the Government of Yukon’s Economic Resilience Plan, published in March 2021, it was mentioned that as of 30th October 2020, the program approved $1,872,866 CAD ($1404497.95 USD) in compensation to 43 businesses for 31 cancelled events. column103: The Chief Medical Officer of Health has said that for Halloween, children should wear non-medical face masks or coverings.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130115233if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/september-30-2020-covid-19-update

column81: On 9th November, the Government of Yukon announced a new support package for the aviation industry so that it can continue providing essential services to and from the territory and its remote communities. Air North will receive up to $5.7 million CAD. Alkan Air will receive up to $300,000 CAD. Charter and rotary carriers may receive up to $1.1 million CAD to support essential service operations. This amounts to a total of $7.1 million CAD ($5,470,890.88 USD) to be spent by the Government of Yukon in support of the aviation industry.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201207002813if_/https://yukon.ca/en/news/new-support-yukons-aviation-industry

column42: Policy remains unchanged.   Gatherings of 10 people can occur indoors,  50 people outdoors, with 2m social distancing between guests not in the same bubble.  Organised gatherings ("defined as seated events in a rented venue") can host 50 people indoors. These gatherings can host 100 people outdoors, with social distancing. column115: On 17th November, restrictions were further eased for visitors to long term care facilities in the Yukon. column69: It was announced on 18th November that as of 5pm on 20th November, all those entering Yukon must undergo 14 days self-isolation. This now includes those arriving from British Columbia,  Nunavut and the Northwest Territories.    Exceptions are made for critical service workers, those travelling from border areas, and those exercising an Aboriginal or treaty right (but this exception can be made for them only for the time needed to exercise that right). column103: As of 23rd November, face masks must be worn on Whitehorse public transit  (the only inner-city public transit system in Yukon). A few exceptions are made for: those with an underlying medical condition or disability which prevents them from wearing a mask; anyone unable to wear or remove a mask without help; children under 5; police or first responders during an emergency.    Source: https://web.archive.org/web/20201130113621/https://www.whitehorse.ca/Home/Components/News/News/4618/31?backlist=%2F

column81: On 24th November, the Government of Yukon announced that the Yukon Essential Workers Income Support Program will be extended to 15th February, 2021. From the program's inception until 24th November, more than $1.2 million CAD ($921,075.85 USD) had been spent on the program. Please note: as it was not known how much would be spent on the programme at its inception on May 22nd, this spending was not accounted for in the corresponding data note and so has been included in this one instead. column81: On 30th November, the Tourism and Culture Minister announced the Tourism Non-Accommodation Sector Supplement, which will provide $1 million CAD ($770,488.61) of funding. Also announced on 30th November was the Culture and Tourism Non-Profit Sector Supplement, for which $300,000 CAD ($231,146.58 USD) has been made available. column90: On 4th December, the Chief Medical Officer of Health announced that from 7th December, restaurants and bars throughout Yukon must keep a daily list of patrons, to help with contact tracing. column79: The Ministerial Order from 11th June still applies. This Order protects tenants who either has to follow a Covid-19 health-protection measure after 25th June, or who owe back rent as a result of losing income due to Covid-19 between 26th March and 25th June. The Order prevents a landlord from evicting a tenant who has breached the tenancy agreement or the Residential Landlord and Tenant Act as a result of the tenant following a health-protection order.    The Order also allows tenants who have rent arrears as a result of them following a health-protection order after 25th June, to pay before 31st December. If a tenant owes rent from 26th March to 25th June as a result of them, or a household member following a health-protection measure, or due to loss of income as a result of Covid-19, they must also pay the rent owed before 31st December.    Source: https://archive.vn/jPatg    http://web.archive.org/web/20201206182335/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/economic-and-social-supports-covid-19/paying-rent-loans-or

column81: On 14th December, the Government of Yukon announced a Covid-19 relief and recovery plan for the tourism sector, the 'Tourism Relief and Recovery Plan' which will involve investments of up to $15 million CAD ($11,730,788.72 USD) in the sector over three years. column94: The Government of Yukon published the 'Yukon’s COVID-19 Vaccine Strategy' in December. On page 11 of this document, it is stated that "The Government of Canada has taken a leadership role for the country’s approach to immunization, working with provinces and territories to ensure there is a coordinated, equitable approach across Canada". Following this statement, the Federal responsibilities for immunisation are outlined. Vaccine investment is not among these responsibilities, indicating that this is a national responsibility.     Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20201216140809/https://yukon.ca/sites/yukon.ca/files/hss/hss-imgs/yukon_vaccine_strategy_fnl.pdf

column74: In addition to the Canadian border generally being closed to non-essential travel, or to those without permission to enter Canada, Canada has banned all travel from the UK as of the 20th December due to the new variant of COVID. column69: On 22nd December, the Chief Medical Officer for Health announced new options for those visiting Yukon undergoing self-isolation in a household with others.     The update states that visitors do not need to socially distance within a household whilst they are undergoing 14 days self-isolation if the rest of the household are self-isolating with them. In this scenario, if the visitor in the household leaves Yukon before their 14-day isolation has come to an end, the rest of the household is allowed to end their self-isolation three days after their guest has left, so long as they monitor themselves and check in with their former guest to see if they have Covid-19 symptoms. If neither are symptomatic after three days, the household can end their self-isolation.    If however, while a household's guest is self-isolating, others in the household do not self-isolate themselves, the guest must socially distance at all times from the rest of the household at a distance of two metres.    Source: http://web.archive.org/web/20210103134028if_/https://yukon.ca/en/health-and-wellness/covid-19-information/latest-updates-covid-19/chief-medical-officer-of-health-covid-19-updates

column88: Each province and territory (PT) is responsible for determining its own testing criteria and procedures, as  well as ensuring adequate supply of testing kits; thus, testing guidelines and capacity have varied across  PTs.     https://web.archive.org/web/20201203171837/https://ihpme.utoronto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Canada-COVID19-HSRM_20200901.pdf
column117: Further, the federal government has communicated that those aged 65 and over and with compromised  immune systems and/or underlying medical conditions pose the highest risk to more severe outcomes  from COVID-19 (PHAC, 2020m). Deaths in long-term care and seniors’ homes have accounted for threequarters of COVID-19-related deaths in the country, to date (Hsu et al., 2020). While the provision of longterm care services is generally the responsibility of PT governments, PHAC has strongly advised organizations supporting these populations to work with staff to limit their work to a single facility,  support staff to allow them to avoid working if symptomatic, discontinue any planned outings for  residents, follow the recommendations for infection prevention and control and to not allow visits or nonessential on-site services at their facilities (except under compassionate or special circumstances), (PHAC, 2020u)    https://web.archive.org/web/20201203171837/https://ihpme.utoronto.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/10/Canada-COVID19-HSRM_20200901.pdf

column86: At the federal level, the Public Health Agency of Canada (PHAC) developed a guide on community based measures for provincial and territorial (PT) public health authorities for mitigating the spread of  COVID-19 (PHAC, 2020d). It is not clear when this guide was first published but it was most updated on  March 25, 2020. It provided the following recommendations for social/physical distancing,  defined as measures taken to minimize close contact with other individuals in the community: avoid  crowded places, avoid non-essential travel, maintain a 2-meter physical separation from individuals not  in your household, avoid physical contact-based greetings (e.g. handshakes), high-risk individuals are  encouraged to stay home unless necessary, and limit the number of individuals gathering in one place (as  per PT regulations)     https://web.archive.org/web/20200325144417/https://www.canada.ca/en/public-health/services/diseases/2019-novel-coronavirus-infection/health-professionals/public-health-measures-mitigate-covid-19.html

column81: 21 April    Small Business and Community Support Measures:  Canada’s Regional Development Agencies (RDAs) are the front line for economic development in Canada and help to address key economic challenges by providing regionally tailored programs, services, knowledge and expertise.    There are six RDAs across the country (the Canadian Northern Economic Development Agency, Western Economic Diversification Canada, FedNor, FedDev Ontario, Canada Economic Development for Quebec Regions and the Atlantic Canada Opportunities Agency).    The government will provide $675 million to support their work, and the businesses and workers they help. This will enable the RDAs to provide equivalent bridge financing support to businesses unable to access the government’s broader support measures.    In response to the effect that COVID-19 may have on rural communities and businesses, the government is also providing $287 million for the Community Futures Network, funded through the RDAs, to support rural businesses and communities, including through access to capital. column33: For the first time in a public statement, the Chief Public Health Officer of Canada, recommended to avoid large crowds and gatherings. This is not an outright recommendation to cancel events, but fits better here in C3 than in C4 as there is no number of people suggested.     In addition to keeping two-metres physical distance from others, washing our hands frequently, and covering coughs and sneezes, we can avoid or limit settings and situations that increase our risk of exposure to the virus, remember:    outdoor spaces are better than inside – avoid or limit time in enclosed spaces,  less people are better than more – avoid crowds and large gatherings,  avoiding close contact is best but when you can't keep your two-metre distance, wearing a non-medical mask or face covering can provide an additional layer of protection.   Learn more on how to safely use a non-medical mask or face covering here: COVID-19: How to safely use a non-medical mask or face covering  Non-medical masks may not be ideal for all conditions. Summer can bring extreme heat and humidity in areas of Canada, which can put you at risk for heat-related illness and make breathing difficult. When the weather is hot and humid, it is best to maintain physical distancing outdoors and reserve your non-medical mask for use indoors and short periods when you can't maintain a 2-metre distance from others.  Finally, because COVID-19 activity and precautions are not the same everywhere in the country, be sure to consult with and follow the advice of the local public health authority where you are.     https://archive.ph/AmHEy

column106: Canada began vaccinations with the Pfizer vaccine on Monday, 14 December to elderly people and front-line workers. Each province will determine their own roll-out plan for those categories of peoples. Vaccinations are Government funded.     British Columbia: The first vaccines will be given in the Vancouver Coastal Health region, and the Fraser Health region.    The doses are going to people working in long-term care homes and assisted living facilities, as well as those in high-risk environments such as hospital emergency wards and intensive care units (ICU).    Alberta: The first vaccines will be given at the University of Alberta Hospital and Royal Alexandra Hospital in Edmonton, and the Peter Lougheed Centre and the Foothills Medical Centre in Calgary.    The doses are going to ICU doctors and nurses, respiratory therapists and long-term care workers.    Saskatchewan: The first vaccines will be given at the Regina General Hospital.    The doses are going to health-care workers in ICUs, emergency and COVID-19 units. Some quantity of the immunization will also go to staff of COVID-19 testing centres as well.    Manitoba: The first vaccines will be given in Winnipeg.    The doses are going to health-care workers most directly involved in COVID-19 response such as those in critical care units, and then to senior citizens in long-term care homes and assisted living facilities.    Ontario: The first vaccines will be given at the Ottawa Hospital and the University Health Network in Toronto.  The doses are going to health-care workers providing care in long-term care homes and other high-risk settings.    Quebec: The first vaccines will be given in Montreal.  The doses are going to residents of a few long-term care homes in the area, followed by health professionals.    New Brunswick: The first vaccines will be given at the Miramichi Regional Hospital.  The doses are going to long-term care residents and staff, health-care workers who respond to COVID-19 outbreaks, extra-mural staff and paramedics, other health-care workers, First Nations nurses, and seniors over 85.    Nova Scotia: The first vaccines will be given in Halifax.  The doses are going to workers in COVID-19 care units, regional care units, and intensive care units that treat COVID-19 patients.    Newfoundland and Labrador: The first vaccines will be given in St. John’s.  It remains unclear who the first vaccines will be given to.    Prince Edward Island: Vaccinations begin on 16 December     The doses are going to priority groups in line with the National Advisory Committee on Immunization’s recommendations, which suggests in no order that vaccines go first to: residents and staff in seniors’ facilities; adults 80 years of age and older; health-care workers with high exposure risks; and Indigenous communities.    The territories: On Wednesday, federal health officials said that due to the Pfizer vaccine’s temperature sensitivity and requirements for advanced cold storage inside a medical facility, the territories will not be receiving any of the initial doses. Territorial leaders have opted to wait for the likely second vaccine to be approved, from Moderna.    https://archive.vn/I7Zm3  https://archive.vn/wip/EumZc
